1
00:02:02,372 --> 00:02:03,831
Thirty thousand.

2
00:02:03,916 --> 00:02:05,249
From the Russians ?

3
00:02:05,334 --> 00:02:06,793
No, from the French.

4
00:02:06,877 --> 00:02:10,296
From the Russians, we capture more than that every day.

5
00:02:29,233 --> 00:02:31,025
Mr. Postman.

6
00:02:32,069 --> 00:02:35,238
War is war and schnapps is
schnapps, but business must go on.

7
00:02:35,405 --> 00:02:37,125
You didn't leave the mail yet this morning.

8
00:02:37,149 --> 00:02:39,484
Ah, I'm sorry, Mr. Meyer.

9
00:02:43,163 --> 00:02:45,581
Hello, Himmelstoss. Anything for us today ?

10
00:02:45,666 --> 00:02:46,749
No, no, Master Peter.

11
00:02:46,834 --> 00:02:48,074
C'mon, there must be something.

12
00:02:48,098 --> 00:02:50,349
Here, here you go, young rascal.

13
00:02:50,629 --> 00:02:53,548
There. This is the last mail I deliver, anyhow.

14
00:02:53,632 --> 00:02:54,632
What ?

15
00:02:54,716 --> 00:02:56,259
Tomorrow I change uniform.

16
00:02:56,343 --> 00:02:57,383
You're going in the army ?

17
00:02:57,427 --> 00:02:58,845
Yes, I was called.

18
00:02:58,929 --> 00:03:01,180
I'm a Sergeant in the reserves, you know.

19
00:03:01,265 --> 00:03:03,683
I'll be called myself, if it doesn't end in a few months.

20
00:03:03,767 --> 00:03:04,767
It will, though.

21
00:03:04,852 --> 00:03:06,644
I'm sure you're right, Mr. Meyer.

22
00:04:09,875 --> 00:04:11,459
...and join the mighty army

23
00:04:11,543 --> 00:04:14,629
that is defending our country, our fatherland.

24
00:04:14,713 --> 00:04:18,466
Now, my beloved class, this is what we must do.

25
00:04:18,926 --> 00:04:21,135
Strike with all our power.

26
00:04:21,219 --> 00:04:23,304
Give every ounce of strength

27
00:04:23,388 --> 00:04:26,807
to win victory before the end of the year.

28
00:04:27,517 --> 00:04:31,312
It is with reluctance that I bring this subject up again.

29
00:04:32,230 --> 00:04:35,816
You are the life of the fatherland, you boys.

30
00:04:35,901 --> 00:04:38,945
You are the iron men of Germany.

31
00:04:39,029 --> 00:04:42,907
You are the gay heroes who will repulse the enemy

32
00:04:42,991 --> 00:04:45,326
when you are called upon to do so.

33
00:04:45,410 --> 00:04:48,329
It is not for me to suggest that any of you

34
00:04:48,413 --> 00:04:52,083
should stand up and offer to defend his country.

35
00:04:52,167 --> 00:04:55,336
But I wonder if such a thing is going through your heads.

36
00:04:55,671 --> 00:04:58,589
I know that in one of the schools

37
00:04:58,674 --> 00:05:01,175
the boys have risen up in the classroom

38
00:05:01,259 --> 00:05:03,260
and enlisted in a mass.

39
00:05:03,553 --> 00:05:06,263
But, of course, if such a thing should happen here

40
00:05:06,348 --> 00:05:09,350
you would not blame me for a feeling of pride.

41
00:05:09,434 --> 00:05:11,560
Perhaps some will say

42
00:05:11,645 --> 00:05:13,813
that you should not be allowed to go yet,

43
00:05:13,897 --> 00:05:18,818
that you are too young, that
you have homes, mothers, fathers,

44
00:05:18,902 --> 00:05:21,112
that you should not be torn away.

45
00:05:21,196 --> 00:05:25,408
Are your fathers so forgetful of their fatherland

46
00:05:25,492 --> 00:05:28,577
that they would let it perish rather than you ?

47
00:05:30,038 --> 00:05:34,125
Are your mothers so weak that they cannot send a son

48
00:05:34,209 --> 00:05:36,919
to defend the land which gave them birth ?

49
00:05:37,004 --> 00:05:40,631
And after all, is a little experience

50
00:05:40,716 --> 00:05:43,259
such a bad thing for a boy ?

51
00:05:44,511 --> 00:05:47,805
Is the honor of wearing a uniform

52
00:05:47,889 --> 00:05:50,391
something from which we should run ?

53
00:05:50,851 --> 00:05:54,311
And if our young ladies glory in those who wear it,

54
00:05:54,396 --> 00:05:56,856
is that anything to be ashamed of ?

55
00:05:56,940 --> 00:06:01,569
I know you have never desired the adulation of heroes.

56
00:06:02,029 --> 00:06:04,697
That has not been part of my teaching.

57
00:06:05,240 --> 00:06:08,034
We have sought to make ourselves worthy

58
00:06:08,118 --> 00:06:10,911
and let acclaim come when it would.

59
00:06:11,496 --> 00:06:14,331
But to be foremost in battle

60
00:06:14,916 --> 00:06:17,460
is a virtue not to be despised.

61
00:06:18,587 --> 00:06:20,713
I believe it will be a quick war,

62
00:06:20,797 --> 00:06:22,631
that there will be few losses.

63
00:06:22,716 --> 00:06:24,967
But if losses there must be,

64
00:06:25,052 --> 00:06:28,137
then let us remember the Latin phrase

65
00:06:28,221 --> 00:06:31,348
which must have come to the lips of many a Roman

66
00:06:31,433 --> 00:06:34,643
when he stood embattled in a foreign land,

67
00:06:35,020 --> 00:06:39,190
"Dulce et decorum est pro patria mori."

68
00:06:39,983 --> 00:06:44,612
"Sweet and fitting it is to die for the fatherland."

69
00:06:46,490 --> 00:06:48,908
Some of you may have ambitions.

70
00:06:48,992 --> 00:06:53,287
I know of one young man who has great promise as a writer

71
00:06:53,997 --> 00:06:56,749
and he has written the first act of a tragedy

72
00:06:56,833 --> 00:06:59,460
which would be a credit to one of the masters.

73
00:06:59,711 --> 00:07:01,796
And he is dreaming, I suppose,

74
00:07:01,880 --> 00:07:06,092
of following in the footsteps of Goethe and Schiller,

75
00:07:06,635 --> 00:07:08,135
and I hope he will.

76
00:07:08,595 --> 00:07:11,180
But now our country calls.

77
00:07:11,264 --> 00:07:13,682
The fatherland needs leaders.

78
00:07:13,767 --> 00:07:17,353
Personal ambition must be thrown aside

79
00:07:17,437 --> 00:07:21,065
in the one great sacrifice for our country.

80
00:07:22,067 --> 00:07:25,903
Here is a glorious beginning for your lives.

81
00:07:25,987 --> 00:07:28,531
The field of honor calls you.

82
00:07:28,615 --> 00:07:30,699
Why are we here ?

83
00:07:30,992 --> 00:07:33,869
You, Kropp, what has kept you back ?

84
00:07:33,995 --> 00:07:38,332
You, Mueller, you know how much you are needed ?

85
00:07:38,416 --> 00:07:42,002
Ah, I see you look at your leader.

86
00:07:43,171 --> 00:07:47,216
And I, too, look to you, Paul Bäumer,

87
00:07:47,634 --> 00:07:49,927
and I wonder what you are going to do.

88
00:07:50,387 --> 00:07:52,012
I'll go. I want to go.

89
00:07:52,097 --> 00:07:53,097
Count on me.

90
00:07:53,515 --> 00:07:54,515
Me, too.

91
00:07:55,433 --> 00:07:56,433
I'm ready.

92
00:07:56,810 --> 00:07:58,227
I'm not gonna stay home.

93
00:08:07,529 --> 00:08:10,865
Follow me ! Enlist now !

94
00:08:10,949 --> 00:08:14,034
No more classes !

95
00:08:15,287 --> 00:08:17,538
Don't be a quitter. Come on, Behn !

96
00:08:17,622 --> 00:08:19,665
Stick together. That's what we've got to do.

97
00:08:19,749 --> 00:08:21,208
Let's all stick together.

98
00:08:21,293 --> 00:08:22,751
Come on, Behn.

99
00:08:23,920 --> 00:08:26,172
All right. All right.

100
00:08:26,506 --> 00:08:27,548
I'll go.

101
00:08:27,632 --> 00:08:28,674
That's the way !

102
00:08:28,758 --> 00:08:30,676
Let's go !

103
00:08:32,179 --> 00:08:34,305
Sing ! Let's sing ! Come on !

104
00:10:08,024 --> 00:10:09,608
Keep in line, there, soldiers.

105
00:10:09,693 --> 00:10:12,569
Anything you say, General.

106
00:10:14,406 --> 00:10:16,073
Detail, halt !

107
00:10:16,950 --> 00:10:18,701
Left face !

108
00:10:19,286 --> 00:10:21,870
Get into uniform, ready to report. Fall out.

109
00:10:38,555 --> 00:10:40,889
I bet you a place like this gets you in good condition.

110
00:10:40,974 --> 00:10:42,725
You have to be for the long marches.

111
00:10:42,809 --> 00:10:45,060
I'm gonna get in the cavalry and ride.

112
00:10:45,562 --> 00:10:47,604
No cavalry for me.

113
00:10:47,689 --> 00:10:49,982
Infantry's where you see the fighting.

114
00:10:50,567 --> 00:10:52,818
Where are all the guns ? That's what I want to know.

115
00:10:52,902 --> 00:10:54,702
Oh, you don't get a gun for a long while yet.

116
00:10:54,946 --> 00:10:58,365
Well, if I'm gonna bump off the
enemy, I gotta have some practice.

117
00:10:58,450 --> 00:10:59,616
Ow !

118
00:11:00,452 --> 00:11:02,578
Bayonet drill. That's what I want.

119
00:11:05,749 --> 00:11:08,250
You won a medal that time, Mueller.

120
00:11:08,418 --> 00:11:11,420
You wait. In about a month, I'll be covered with them.

121
00:11:12,589 --> 00:11:14,506
Say, keep your boots out of my face.

122
00:11:14,591 --> 00:11:17,760
Why, it's an honor to have those boots in your face.

123
00:11:17,927 --> 00:11:21,597
They're the best pair in the army. My uncle gave them to me.

124
00:11:21,848 --> 00:11:24,433
Just look at that special imported leather.

125
00:11:24,768 --> 00:11:27,603
Put them anyplace you like, except in my face.

126
00:11:28,104 --> 00:11:30,773
Not even a kitchen maid'll look at me in this.

127
00:11:31,816 --> 00:11:32,816
Attention !

128
00:11:35,612 --> 00:11:37,863
Well, for the love of... It's Himmelstoss !

129
00:11:37,947 --> 00:11:39,031
So it is.

130
00:11:39,115 --> 00:11:40,449
And all dressed up.

131
00:11:40,742 --> 00:11:41,867
Hello, Himmie.

132
00:11:41,951 --> 00:11:44,661
You didn't think you'd see me again so soon, did you ?

133
00:11:46,664 --> 00:11:47,664
You see my rank ?

134
00:11:47,749 --> 00:11:49,208
Sure.

135
00:11:49,292 --> 00:11:50,959
Fall back, then !

136
00:11:51,057 --> 00:11:52,897
Himmelstoss, we certainly are glad to see you.

137
00:11:52,921 --> 00:11:54,046
What did you say ?

138
00:11:54,130 --> 00:11:55,839
I was going to say... Never mind !

139
00:11:55,924 --> 00:11:57,564
What's the matter with you, Himmelstoss ?

140
00:11:57,588 --> 00:11:59,885
When you address your superior officer, say "Sir."

141
00:11:59,965 --> 00:12:01,405
Where'd he get such a nice uniform ?

142
00:12:01,429 --> 00:12:02,989
Will there be any mail for us, Himmie ?

143
00:12:03,013 --> 00:12:03,806
Quiet !

144
00:12:03,890 --> 00:12:05,182
My dear fellow, you're shouting.

145
00:12:05,266 --> 00:12:07,559
Come on, Himmelstoss. We know you.

146
00:12:07,644 --> 00:12:09,478
Take off the false whiskers.

147
00:12:10,980 --> 00:12:12,147
I believe you mean it.

148
00:12:12,232 --> 00:12:14,066
You'll find out that I mean it.

149
00:12:14,150 --> 00:12:15,950
But only three days ago you were our postman.

150
00:12:16,027 --> 00:12:17,152
Silence !

151
00:12:18,321 --> 00:12:19,905
Come back here !

152
00:12:24,869 --> 00:12:26,286
Line up !

153
00:12:26,996 --> 00:12:30,624
Line up ! Get in some kind of a
line ! Don't even think about it.

154
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:33,585
All of you ! Line up, I say !

155
00:12:46,182 --> 00:12:47,182
Hmm.

156
00:12:49,436 --> 00:12:51,687
What a pretty sight that is.

157
00:12:52,105 --> 00:12:54,606
Have you never heard of standing in line ?

158
00:12:54,899 --> 00:12:56,567
You make a fine mess of it.

159
00:12:56,651 --> 00:12:58,819
Well, I'll have to teach you.

160
00:12:59,028 --> 00:13:01,447
We'll spend the whole day on it, huh ?

161
00:13:02,824 --> 00:13:05,826
You may be stupid, but I'm used to that.

162
00:13:05,910 --> 00:13:09,538
And then there'll be plenty of other things, too.

163
00:13:09,622 --> 00:13:11,707
Oh, I'll not neglect you.

164
00:13:12,959 --> 00:13:13,959
Hmm.

165
00:13:14,711 --> 00:13:17,671
You're not much to begin with, but I'll do my best.

166
00:13:19,632 --> 00:13:23,218
I see that we have come here with a slight misunderstanding,

167
00:13:23,303 --> 00:13:26,054
and we'll correct that, too, won't we, huh ?

168
00:13:26,806 --> 00:13:30,851
And the first thing to do is to
forget everything you ever knew.

169
00:13:30,935 --> 00:13:33,604
Everything you ever learned, forget ! See ?

170
00:13:34,522 --> 00:13:37,941
Forget what you've been and
what you think you're going to be.

171
00:13:38,067 --> 00:13:40,944
You're going to be soldiers, and that's all !

172
00:13:41,446 --> 00:13:44,907
I'll take the mother's milk out
of you. I'll make you hard-boiled.

173
00:13:44,991 --> 00:13:47,951
I'll make soldiers out of you or kill you !

174
00:13:48,661 --> 00:13:51,747
Now, salute !

175
00:13:56,503 --> 00:13:58,837
Attention !

176
00:14:04,385 --> 00:14:07,554
Detachment, lie down !

177
00:14:07,639 --> 00:14:09,056
Down !

178
00:14:17,440 --> 00:14:19,316
Head down !

179
00:14:19,400 --> 00:14:20,859
Keep your head down, Bäumer !

180
00:14:24,155 --> 00:14:26,740
Detachment, get up !

181
00:14:28,785 --> 00:14:30,202
Advance !

182
00:14:39,671 --> 00:14:41,004
Now, sing !

183
00:14:49,514 --> 00:14:52,015
Do you call that singing ?

184
00:14:52,100 --> 00:14:54,393
Detachment, halt !

185
00:14:58,398 --> 00:15:01,567
So, we have no spirit, huh ?

186
00:15:02,277 --> 00:15:04,194
We are in no mood for recreation.

187
00:15:04,279 --> 00:15:06,154
Work is what we want. Good !

188
00:15:06,823 --> 00:15:09,116
Then we'll go back to work.

189
00:15:14,289 --> 00:15:17,708
Detachment, lie down !

190
00:15:19,085 --> 00:15:20,919
Keep your head down.

191
00:15:23,923 --> 00:15:25,716
Now, sing !

192
00:15:56,581 --> 00:15:58,415
Men, halt !

193
00:15:58,958 --> 00:16:00,667
Order, arms !

194
00:16:02,462 --> 00:16:05,339
Inspection at 3:00. Dismissed !

195
00:16:11,304 --> 00:16:14,890
Oh, that swine ! That means we get no time off.

196
00:16:14,974 --> 00:16:17,851
It will take four hours to get ready for inspection.

197
00:16:18,144 --> 00:16:19,686
I'd like to know what's in his mind.

198
00:16:19,771 --> 00:16:20,812
He hasn't got any !

199
00:16:20,897 --> 00:16:22,898
I'm gonna cut him open sometime and find out.

200
00:16:22,982 --> 00:16:25,150
He's too thick-skinned. He won't cut.

201
00:16:25,610 --> 00:16:28,487
This is the fourth time he's
made me disappoint that poor girl.

202
00:16:31,532 --> 00:16:33,158
Arms !

203
00:16:33,242 --> 00:16:35,243
Order, arms !

204
00:16:35,703 --> 00:16:37,579
Left shoulder, arms !

205
00:16:38,581 --> 00:16:40,582
Squad, right. To the right, march !

206
00:16:40,667 --> 00:16:44,002
Left, left, left, left.

207
00:16:49,967 --> 00:16:52,761
Column, left, march !

208
00:16:52,929 --> 00:16:54,221
Left, hut...

209
00:16:55,598 --> 00:16:57,641
Squad, left march !

210
00:17:00,269 --> 00:17:02,938
Forward, march ! Left.

211
00:17:05,274 --> 00:17:08,235
Detachment, halt !

212
00:17:08,945 --> 00:17:10,821
Present arms !

213
00:17:13,658 --> 00:17:15,242
Himmelstoss.

214
00:17:17,954 --> 00:17:20,539
Excellent work. They're going up front tomorrow.

215
00:17:20,623 --> 00:17:22,791
I recommend leave till midnight.

216
00:17:22,875 --> 00:17:24,251
Very good, Sir.

217
00:17:26,587 --> 00:17:28,380
Left shoulders, arms !

218
00:17:28,464 --> 00:17:33,635
Forward march. Left, left, straight ahead !

219
00:17:33,720 --> 00:17:35,137
Now, left.

220
00:17:39,308 --> 00:17:40,434
We're clear.

221
00:17:48,067 --> 00:17:50,902
Left, left, left.

222
00:17:50,987 --> 00:17:54,281
Detachment, lie down !

223
00:17:55,950 --> 00:17:57,826
Crawl forward !

224
00:18:03,166 --> 00:18:06,585
He spoiled our leave. I'll never forgive him for that.

225
00:18:06,669 --> 00:18:08,462
The rat !

226
00:18:08,546 --> 00:18:10,756
Leave till midnight.

227
00:18:10,840 --> 00:18:13,467
It'll take till midnight to dry our clothes.

228
00:18:14,802 --> 00:18:16,178
There goes the filthy ape now.

229
00:18:18,014 --> 00:18:20,515
While we slave over this mud,
he goes off to have a few drinks.

230
00:18:21,350 --> 00:18:24,269
Someday I'm going to take one smack at him, just one.

231
00:18:24,353 --> 00:18:28,273
Me, too. That's gonna be my life's work from now on.

232
00:18:28,357 --> 00:18:31,443
Why only one ? I'm gonna take several.

233
00:18:31,527 --> 00:18:34,863
I might even kick him when he's down. I feel mean.

234
00:18:36,282 --> 00:18:37,783
What are you doing ?

235
00:18:37,867 --> 00:18:39,347
You're not going to desert, are you ?

236
00:18:39,371 --> 00:18:40,580
What ?

237
00:18:47,210 --> 00:18:49,961
Listen. I've got an idea.

238
00:19:01,140 --> 00:19:03,475
Crawl forward. Lie down.

239
00:19:14,362 --> 00:19:16,530
Lie down. Crawl forward.

240
00:19:19,242 --> 00:19:20,700
What ?

241
00:19:41,889 --> 00:19:43,181
Here comes an officer.

242
00:19:45,560 --> 00:19:47,227
Get him out of here.

243
00:21:00,635 --> 00:21:01,927
Cover !

244
00:21:23,032 --> 00:21:24,950
Paul, are you all right ?

245
00:21:25,034 --> 00:21:26,034
You all right ?

246
00:21:26,077 --> 00:21:27,953
Behn ! Behn !

247
00:21:30,790 --> 00:21:33,792
Behn ! Come on !

248
00:21:33,876 --> 00:21:37,128
Behn, come on. You fool, Behn.

249
00:21:37,213 --> 00:21:39,714
Get up ! Come on.

250
00:22:04,407 --> 00:22:06,408
Sounds like more replacements coming in.

251
00:22:06,492 --> 00:22:09,577
Yeah. Tjaden must have gone home for that wood.

252
00:22:16,836 --> 00:22:20,338
Here's some more, fresh from the turnip patch.

253
00:22:20,506 --> 00:22:22,674
I suppose this is where we bunk.

254
00:22:44,447 --> 00:22:47,198
That's me, "I. Westhus,"

255
00:22:47,283 --> 00:22:48,908
and this is where he lives.

256
00:22:49,493 --> 00:22:50,577
I didn't know.

257
00:22:50,953 --> 00:22:52,203
Well, you know now.

258
00:22:53,039 --> 00:22:54,581
Yes. Yes, of course.

259
00:23:01,589 --> 00:23:03,381
It's all right.

260
00:23:03,466 --> 00:23:04,799
Here's a bunk, Paul.

261
00:23:11,599 --> 00:23:12,599
When did we eat last ?

262
00:23:12,641 --> 00:23:13,767
Don't remind me.

263
00:23:13,851 --> 00:23:15,435
I was fine until you spoke.

264
00:23:15,519 --> 00:23:16,895
Where are we, anyway ?

265
00:23:16,978 --> 00:23:19,458
I don't know. The name on the
railroad station's been shot off.

266
00:23:19,482 --> 00:23:21,399
Well, there must be something to eat somewhere.

267
00:23:21,484 --> 00:23:23,234
I'll tell you what I'll do.

268
00:23:23,319 --> 00:23:25,195
I'll ask those fellows.

269
00:23:33,245 --> 00:23:36,664
Sorry to disturb you, Mr. Westhus.

270
00:23:36,832 --> 00:23:41,086
Oh, meet Detering. A better farmer never lived.

271
00:23:41,587 --> 00:23:42,629
And Mr. Tjaden.

272
00:23:42,713 --> 00:23:43,755
Sit down.

273
00:23:44,840 --> 00:23:47,175
You see, we haven't eaten since breakfast.

274
00:23:47,259 --> 00:23:49,779
We thought maybe you could
tell us what we ought to do about it.

275
00:23:49,803 --> 00:23:51,721
Eat without further delay.

276
00:23:54,391 --> 00:23:56,351
Well, what's funny about that ?

277
00:23:57,019 --> 00:23:59,813
This is a bad town to bring an appetite to, soldier.

278
00:23:59,897 --> 00:24:01,457
We've been here since yesterday morning

279
00:24:01,481 --> 00:24:03,899
and we've been living on baled hay and razor blades.

280
00:24:04,068 --> 00:24:07,445
We're willing to buy our food. Where's the canteen ?

281
00:24:08,864 --> 00:24:10,406
The only canteen in these regions

282
00:24:10,491 --> 00:24:12,033
is out looking for supplies.

283
00:24:12,118 --> 00:24:13,493
Ever hear of Katczinsky ?

284
00:24:13,577 --> 00:24:14,702
Who ?

285
00:24:14,870 --> 00:24:17,580
Katczinsky. He's uncanny.

286
00:24:17,665 --> 00:24:21,292
If there's any food within 25
miles, he'll be the one to get it.

287
00:24:27,550 --> 00:24:29,050
Hey !

288
00:24:46,110 --> 00:24:54,110
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

289
00:25:04,837 --> 00:25:06,254
Attention !

290
00:25:11,760 --> 00:25:12,760
What is this ?

291
00:25:13,596 --> 00:25:16,181
Volunteers for the future general staff.

292
00:25:19,351 --> 00:25:22,478
Sometime I'm gonna take one of you volunteers apart

293
00:25:22,563 --> 00:25:26,191
and find out what makes you leave school and join the Army.

294
00:25:27,193 --> 00:25:29,777
At ease. This is no parade ground.

295
00:25:33,616 --> 00:25:35,325
- Hungry ?
- Yes.

296
00:25:35,451 --> 00:25:38,870
Wait ! Wait a minute. Wait a minute. That's no invitation.

297
00:25:38,954 --> 00:25:40,038
Can you pay ?

298
00:25:40,122 --> 00:25:42,207
Yeah, sure. I have some money.

299
00:25:42,291 --> 00:25:46,044
No, not money. That's just pieces of paper.

300
00:25:46,795 --> 00:25:48,671
Have you got any cigarettes, cigars,

301
00:25:48,797 --> 00:25:50,340
or soap, cognac...

302
00:25:50,424 --> 00:25:51,466
Yeah, yeah. Yeah.

303
00:25:51,550 --> 00:25:53,301
Chewing tobacco ? Yeah, yeah.

304
00:25:53,385 --> 00:25:54,427
Hey, Kat ! Yeah ?

305
00:25:54,511 --> 00:25:56,971
Are you crazy ? There ain't enough here for us.

306
00:25:57,973 --> 00:25:59,933
I wish you three would get bumped off.

307
00:26:00,017 --> 00:26:02,310
I'm tired of feeding you for nothing.

308
00:26:02,436 --> 00:26:04,187
Bring everything you've got.

309
00:26:07,066 --> 00:26:08,126
I'm so hungry...

310
00:26:08,150 --> 00:26:09,294
I'd be glad to give you...

311
00:26:09,318 --> 00:26:10,485
Come on !

312
00:26:10,569 --> 00:26:12,403
Is this enough, Sir ?

313
00:26:27,253 --> 00:26:28,670
Kat ! Hmm ?

314
00:26:28,754 --> 00:26:30,234
You've got the wiring detail tonight.

315
00:26:30,258 --> 00:26:31,089
Where ?

316
00:26:31,173 --> 00:26:32,423
Past the graveyard.

317
00:26:32,508 --> 00:26:33,675
With this bunch ?

318
00:26:33,759 --> 00:26:36,636
It's quiet tonight. You can teach them a couple of things.

319
00:26:36,720 --> 00:26:38,471
Thanks. I'd rather do it alone.

320
00:26:38,555 --> 00:26:40,932
These babes get killed off too fast.

321
00:26:41,016 --> 00:26:42,475
Well, the lorry's waiting.

322
00:26:42,559 --> 00:26:44,435
Last night I was too hungry to sleep

323
00:26:44,520 --> 00:26:46,560
and tonight, when I get the wrinkles out of my gut,

324
00:26:46,584 --> 00:26:48,189
they think up wiring duty.

325
00:26:48,274 --> 00:26:51,025
Well, here's your chance, heroes.

326
00:26:51,110 --> 00:26:53,152
For the fatherland !

327
00:26:53,237 --> 00:26:56,072
Come on, get your stuff and let's get out of here.

328
00:27:18,012 --> 00:27:19,429
Is that any way to drive ?

329
00:27:19,513 --> 00:27:21,514
Let him drive any way he wants.

330
00:27:21,598 --> 00:27:25,059
Suppose he breaks your arm. You get sent home, don't you ?

331
00:27:25,144 --> 00:27:27,895
A lot better than having a hole in your guts.

332
00:27:43,662 --> 00:27:46,664
If there's any of you left, I'll pick you up in the morning.

333
00:27:46,749 --> 00:27:49,542
Well, if that ride you gave us didn't kill us, nothing will.

334
00:27:49,626 --> 00:27:52,920
And be on time. I don't want to miss my breakfast.

335
00:28:11,106 --> 00:28:12,106
Yeah ?

336
00:28:12,483 --> 00:28:14,817
You better wait for your army, Papa.

337
00:28:16,653 --> 00:28:19,697
Here, here. Don't be so backward.

338
00:28:20,199 --> 00:28:24,285
Listen, children. All we got
to do is to string a little wire.

339
00:28:24,370 --> 00:28:27,872
We pick it up at the dump and carry it to where we need it.

340
00:28:28,374 --> 00:28:30,500
Now, you're gonna see some shellfire,

341
00:28:30,584 --> 00:28:32,668
and you're gonna be scared, see ?

342
00:28:38,550 --> 00:28:40,718
It's all right, boy. Get up.

343
00:28:46,642 --> 00:28:48,768
Here. Never mind.

344
00:28:48,852 --> 00:28:52,730
It's happened to better men
than you, and it's happened to me.

345
00:28:53,482 --> 00:28:57,318
When we come back, I'll get
you all some nice clean underwear.

346
00:29:01,156 --> 00:29:03,783
That kind of shell you don't have to pay much attention to.

347
00:29:03,867 --> 00:29:06,035
Those big fellows just make a lot of noise

348
00:29:06,120 --> 00:29:08,830
and land about five miles behind the line.

349
00:29:10,332 --> 00:29:13,918
The things we've got to watch out for are the light ones.

350
00:29:14,002 --> 00:29:15,837
They don't give you much warning.

351
00:29:15,921 --> 00:29:19,632
They go "waah zing."

352
00:29:19,716 --> 00:29:22,552
And when you hear that, down !

353
00:29:24,221 --> 00:29:26,222
Mother Earth.

354
00:29:26,765 --> 00:29:29,100
Press yourselves down upon her.

355
00:29:29,685 --> 00:29:32,270
Bury yourselves deep into her.

356
00:29:34,523 --> 00:29:36,190
Just keep your eyes on me.

357
00:29:36,275 --> 00:29:38,776
When you see me flop, you flop.

358
00:29:38,861 --> 00:29:41,696
Only, try to beat me to it.

359
00:30:35,918 --> 00:30:37,210
Now, listen.

360
00:30:38,253 --> 00:30:40,087
I'll show you how it's done.

361
00:30:41,590 --> 00:30:44,759
Give me a couple of those. That's to kill the noise.

362
00:30:44,885 --> 00:30:46,219
Tjaden.

363
00:31:21,672 --> 00:31:22,922
See that ?

364
00:31:23,298 --> 00:31:24,298
What's that mean ?

365
00:31:24,341 --> 00:31:25,591
Bombardment.

366
00:32:01,295 --> 00:32:02,753
My eyes !

367
00:32:04,881 --> 00:32:06,090
I'm blind !

368
00:32:06,174 --> 00:32:08,009
I can't see ! God !

369
00:32:08,093 --> 00:32:10,261
My eyes ! I can't see !

370
00:32:12,848 --> 00:32:13,931
Oh, God !

371
00:32:16,059 --> 00:32:19,186
- It's Behn ! It's Behn !
- I can't see !

372
00:32:28,989 --> 00:32:31,282
I'll go get him... You'll get killed !

373
00:32:31,533 --> 00:32:33,117
Leave him. What ?

374
00:32:34,453 --> 00:32:36,078
Let me... Lay down and stay there !

375
00:32:36,163 --> 00:32:37,363
You'll get your head shot off.

376
00:32:47,257 --> 00:32:50,635
He's dead.

377
00:32:50,719 --> 00:32:52,479
Why did you risk your life bringing him in ?

378
00:32:52,503 --> 00:32:54,004
But it's Behn.

379
00:32:54,556 --> 00:32:55,556
My friend.

380
00:32:55,641 --> 00:32:57,850
It's a corpse, no matter who it is.

381
00:33:00,979 --> 00:33:03,397
Now, don't any of you ever do that again.

382
00:33:03,607 --> 00:33:05,358
Put him over there.

383
00:33:29,091 --> 00:33:30,174
Mind the wire.

384
00:33:30,258 --> 00:33:31,592
Mind the wire.

385
00:33:34,680 --> 00:33:42,680
Mind the wire.

386
00:33:44,439 --> 00:33:46,107
All right, come on.

387
00:33:50,946 --> 00:33:54,115
All right, come on. Get your packs and fall in. Hurry up.

388
00:33:54,616 --> 00:33:57,535
Come on. Hurry up. Come on. Make it snappy.

389
00:33:57,619 --> 00:33:59,453
Get your packs and fall in.

390
00:34:00,789 --> 00:34:03,040
Kat, what are we doing ? What's happening ?

391
00:34:03,125 --> 00:34:04,625
You heard him. Orders to march.

392
00:34:05,127 --> 00:34:06,407
But where to, for the love of...

393
00:34:06,461 --> 00:34:07,878
Another party.

394
00:34:09,297 --> 00:34:12,341
And this one is gonna last a long time.

395
00:34:17,097 --> 00:34:18,347
Come on.

396
00:34:19,641 --> 00:34:21,100
Here we go.

397
00:34:24,104 --> 00:34:26,147
Company, attention !

398
00:34:27,023 --> 00:34:28,941
Shoulder, arms !

399
00:34:31,194 --> 00:34:33,320
March right, march !

400
00:34:57,012 --> 00:34:58,262
Take your hands off that !

401
00:34:58,346 --> 00:34:59,346
Queen takes it !

402
00:34:59,431 --> 00:35:01,348
Well, if you think that's a queen, look again.

403
00:35:01,767 --> 00:35:03,476
It's a Jack.

404
00:35:04,311 --> 00:35:05,311
Yeah.

405
00:35:05,353 --> 00:35:07,563
Honest, these cards all look alike.

406
00:35:09,649 --> 00:35:11,776
It's too noisy ! I can't play.

407
00:35:12,527 --> 00:35:14,403
I suppose your delicate nerves... Get up.

408
00:35:14,488 --> 00:35:15,946
...can't stand it.

409
00:35:21,995 --> 00:35:25,331
That's Oscar. The son of a...

410
00:35:27,334 --> 00:35:28,834
Look at that !

411
00:35:30,128 --> 00:35:32,963
Don't be so snooty. You may wish you had this back.

412
00:35:33,298 --> 00:35:35,090
About two more days of this

413
00:35:36,343 --> 00:35:38,143
and this rat-bitten end of a piece of bread's

414
00:35:38,220 --> 00:35:41,096
gonna taste just like a hunk of fruitcake.

415
00:35:43,517 --> 00:35:46,101
It wouldn't... It wouldn't last two more days, would it ?

416
00:35:46,186 --> 00:35:48,813
Didn't I tell you this was gonna be a bad one ?

417
00:35:49,314 --> 00:35:51,482
I don't mind the days so much.

418
00:35:51,566 --> 00:35:53,901
It's keeping up all night that's...

419
00:35:54,778 --> 00:35:56,946
Two more days makes a week, kid.

420
00:35:57,030 --> 00:35:59,198
Then you can say you've been under fire.

421
00:35:59,282 --> 00:36:01,075
You're not scared, are you ?

422
00:36:01,576 --> 00:36:03,828
No. I was just asking, that's all.

423
00:36:09,584 --> 00:36:11,252
Want to play some more ?

424
00:36:11,336 --> 00:36:12,378
Do you ?

425
00:36:16,216 --> 00:36:17,299
Sure.

426
00:36:17,425 --> 00:36:18,551
All right. My deal.

427
00:36:20,929 --> 00:36:23,889
You better get your boot back before Oscar eats that.

428
00:36:25,809 --> 00:36:27,601
The kid's all right.

429
00:36:33,400 --> 00:36:34,733
Behn.

430
00:36:36,278 --> 00:36:37,403
Behn.

431
00:36:40,574 --> 00:36:43,075
Yeah, yeah. Let him sleep. He's dreaming. Behn.

432
00:36:44,077 --> 00:36:47,246
Oh, God. Can't you see it's Behn ?

433
00:36:47,330 --> 00:36:49,748
He didn't want to come to war.

434
00:36:50,417 --> 00:36:53,043
No, no.

435
00:36:53,503 --> 00:36:54,879
It isn't Behn.

436
00:36:56,089 --> 00:36:57,715
It isn't Behn !

437
00:36:58,925 --> 00:37:01,969
It's Kemmerick ! It's me !

438
00:37:02,053 --> 00:37:04,847
Shut up, will you ? It's bad enough in here as it is.

439
00:37:04,931 --> 00:37:06,098
Every...

440
00:37:06,516 --> 00:37:08,058
Everything's all right, Franz.

441
00:37:08,143 --> 00:37:09,310
You're dreaming.

442
00:37:10,103 --> 00:37:11,520
I see something.

443
00:37:11,605 --> 00:37:12,980
You're just dreaming, I guess.

444
00:37:18,445 --> 00:37:19,945
Attention ! At ease.

445
00:37:21,448 --> 00:37:23,198
The barrage is getting worse.

446
00:37:26,119 --> 00:37:28,203
Men in two more dugouts, gone.

447
00:37:33,251 --> 00:37:37,463
However, we'll do our best to
get some food up here by evening.

448
00:37:59,569 --> 00:38:01,445
Stop !

449
00:38:11,790 --> 00:38:13,165
Let me out.

450
00:38:15,710 --> 00:38:16,794
What did you do that for ?

451
00:38:16,878 --> 00:38:18,837
Shut up ! Grab him.

452
00:38:19,756 --> 00:38:21,340
No. Now hold him.

453
00:38:44,739 --> 00:38:46,448
You all right now ?

454
00:38:46,908 --> 00:38:48,033
I think so.

455
00:38:52,247 --> 00:38:54,289
I couldn't hold out much longer.

456
00:39:14,811 --> 00:39:15,978
Let me out !

457
00:39:17,439 --> 00:39:19,189
It's going to kill me !

458
00:39:20,734 --> 00:39:22,151
Very good.

459
00:39:28,616 --> 00:39:31,201
Oh, my God, it's Franz ! This is terrible !

460
00:39:36,791 --> 00:39:38,391
No, don't. He's been hit in the stomach.

461
00:39:38,415 --> 00:39:39,790
He can't have anything to drink.

462
00:39:39,916 --> 00:39:41,295
Get a stretcher.

463
00:39:44,215 --> 00:39:46,300
Where'd they get you, Kemmerick ?

464
00:39:53,808 --> 00:39:54,808
Here it is, Sir.

465
00:39:54,893 --> 00:39:56,143
Take his head.

466
00:40:00,148 --> 00:40:01,982
All right. Take him out.

467
00:40:05,820 --> 00:40:07,071
Is it serious, Sir ?

468
00:40:07,155 --> 00:40:08,322
I'm not sure.

469
00:40:09,824 --> 00:40:11,450
Tell the others he's all right.

470
00:40:11,534 --> 00:40:12,534
Yes, Sir.

471
00:40:31,513 --> 00:40:34,264
If we're going to fight, why don't we fight ?

472
00:40:34,349 --> 00:40:36,058
Why don't we go over ?

473
00:40:39,521 --> 00:40:41,688
You could go crazy staying here.

474
00:40:44,859 --> 00:40:46,652
Let's do something !

475
00:40:47,028 --> 00:40:48,112
Let's go after them !

476
00:40:48,196 --> 00:40:49,363
Sit down !

477
00:40:53,201 --> 00:40:54,660
If that cook of ours had any guts,

478
00:40:54,744 --> 00:40:57,079
he'd try to bring something through.

479
00:40:58,373 --> 00:41:01,500
He's so far behind the lines he can't hear the shooting !

480
00:41:02,043 --> 00:41:04,336
Here's Kat. Get anything ?

481
00:41:04,420 --> 00:41:05,838
Any luck ?

482
00:41:05,919 --> 00:41:07,399
We'll have to split this up among us.

483
00:41:07,423 --> 00:41:08,966
Something to eat !

484
00:41:16,724 --> 00:41:18,016
We need butter, too.

485
00:41:18,101 --> 00:41:22,062
Yes. And dessert. And a feather bed to sleep on.

486
00:41:31,906 --> 00:41:33,217
- Rats !
- Rats !

487
00:41:33,241 --> 00:41:35,409
Rats. Rats.

488
00:41:37,787 --> 00:41:39,246
Get out of the way !

489
00:41:56,055 --> 00:41:57,347
That's enough.

490
00:41:57,432 --> 00:41:58,807
That's enough, boys.

491
00:42:17,619 --> 00:42:19,077
What's that ?

492
00:42:20,580 --> 00:42:21,580
Come on !

493
00:42:21,623 --> 00:42:23,290
Come on ! Grab your rifles !

494
00:42:25,627 --> 00:42:26,919
Come on !

495
00:42:27,295 --> 00:42:28,420
Come along.

496
00:42:28,588 --> 00:42:29,630
Come on, everybody.

497
00:42:30,590 --> 00:42:31,882
Here they come.

498
00:42:31,966 --> 00:42:33,508
Get your grenades here.

499
00:42:33,593 --> 00:42:34,635
In this space.

500
00:42:34,719 --> 00:42:36,803
Hurry up. This is an attack. Come on, hurry up.

501
00:44:29,417 --> 00:44:31,084
Come on !

502
00:46:33,624 --> 00:46:35,709
Aim. Fire.

503
00:46:52,351 --> 00:46:54,269
Here you go, troops.

504
00:48:04,882 --> 00:48:07,842
Let's go ! Let's go ! Let's move !

505
00:49:08,112 --> 00:49:12,157
We can't hold this position, men. Back to your own lines !

506
00:49:13,242 --> 00:49:15,160
We've got a lift from cavalry.

507
00:49:15,369 --> 00:49:16,620
Now, then.

508
00:50:35,116 --> 00:50:37,033
Fill it up. And hurry up.

509
00:50:37,118 --> 00:50:38,326
I've got other things to do.

510
00:50:38,411 --> 00:50:40,495
I've been waiting for this for three weeks.

511
00:50:40,579 --> 00:50:42,789
When they all get here.

512
00:50:45,126 --> 00:50:46,668
What do you want ?

513
00:50:46,752 --> 00:50:49,295
Beans, you homely-looking son of a frog's leg.

514
00:50:49,380 --> 00:50:51,131
What do you think I want ?

515
00:50:51,841 --> 00:50:52,882
We're hungry.

516
00:50:56,804 --> 00:50:59,889
Shut up ! I'll feed you when you're all here.

517
00:50:59,974 --> 00:51:01,474
We're all here now.

518
00:51:01,559 --> 00:51:04,185
Only half the company's here. Get the rest.

519
00:51:04,270 --> 00:51:05,395
Wake 'em up.

520
00:51:05,479 --> 00:51:06,855
Yeah.

521
00:51:06,939 --> 00:51:10,316
I wish I could wake 'em up. There's 80 of us left.

522
00:51:10,401 --> 00:51:13,945
The rest is in dressing stations or pushing up daisies.

523
00:51:14,071 --> 00:51:17,782
Eighty ? And I cooked for 150 !

524
00:51:18,367 --> 00:51:21,661
All right. We'll have enough for once. Come on, dish out !

525
00:51:22,413 --> 00:51:26,666
You mean, you've cooked beans
for 150, and you've got bread for 150,

526
00:51:26,751 --> 00:51:30,420
and sausage for 150, and tobacco for 150 ?

527
00:51:30,504 --> 00:51:34,090
Everything ! It's all wrong. I should have been notified.

528
00:51:34,175 --> 00:51:37,635
What a feast ! Everyone gets two issues.

529
00:51:38,387 --> 00:51:40,388
Hey, get back in line ! Get back in line !

530
00:51:40,473 --> 00:51:43,016
Oh, no ! That won't do.

531
00:51:43,142 --> 00:51:46,436
I can't give 80 men what's meant for 150.

532
00:51:48,314 --> 00:51:49,856
Listen.

533
00:51:50,441 --> 00:51:53,818
You drew rations for the 2nd Company, didn't you ?

534
00:51:53,903 --> 00:51:55,153
Yeah.

535
00:51:55,488 --> 00:51:57,864
All right. We're the 2nd Company.

536
00:51:59,241 --> 00:52:00,742
I've got my orders.

537
00:52:00,826 --> 00:52:01,951
Kat's right.

538
00:52:02,036 --> 00:52:03,578
We're the 2nd Company.

539
00:52:03,662 --> 00:52:05,822
And if only half of us get back, that's our good luck.

540
00:52:05,846 --> 00:52:06,930
Come on. Dish it out.

541
00:52:07,014 --> 00:52:08,014
Come on !

542
00:52:08,083 --> 00:52:09,083
No !

543
00:52:09,168 --> 00:52:10,710
Hey !

544
00:52:11,295 --> 00:52:14,964
You're the yellowest baboon that ever drew a cook wagon

545
00:52:15,049 --> 00:52:17,258
and you're scared it shows.

546
00:52:17,343 --> 00:52:20,470
All we want to hear out of you is one more little yip

547
00:52:20,554 --> 00:52:23,056
and we'll cut you up and eat you raw.

548
00:52:23,224 --> 00:52:26,142
Why, you keep your kitchen so far back of the lines

549
00:52:26,227 --> 00:52:29,729
we never get anything to eat
until it's cold and we're asleep !

550
00:52:29,814 --> 00:52:34,526
Now, you low-down rat, get out
or we wreck the joint, so help us.

551
00:52:35,152 --> 00:52:37,070
Come on ! Give us our food.

552
00:52:38,405 --> 00:52:39,614
Attention !

553
00:52:46,330 --> 00:52:47,997
At ease.

554
00:52:48,791 --> 00:52:50,041
What's going on here ?

555
00:52:50,125 --> 00:52:53,753
He's cooked for 150, Sir, and he only wants to give us half.

556
00:52:57,633 --> 00:52:58,675
Looks pretty good.

557
00:52:58,759 --> 00:52:59,759
Yes, Sir.

558
00:52:59,802 --> 00:53:02,470
Serve the whole issue ! The men can use it.

559
00:53:02,555 --> 00:53:04,264
Yes, Sir.

560
00:53:04,348 --> 00:53:05,682
And bring me a plate, too.

561
00:53:05,766 --> 00:53:06,933
Yes, Sir.

562
00:53:08,519 --> 00:53:11,104
All right. Take it all. Take everything.

563
00:53:11,188 --> 00:53:13,565
Give 'em honey. Give 'em what they want.

564
00:53:14,859 --> 00:53:17,443
Fill it up ! Fill it up ! Fill it up !

565
00:53:20,698 --> 00:53:22,115
Anybody else ?

566
00:53:22,199 --> 00:53:24,450
All I want is to get going.

567
00:53:56,817 --> 00:53:57,901
Don't mind me.

568
00:53:57,985 --> 00:54:00,403
Oh, that's all right. Don't mention it.

569
00:54:05,034 --> 00:54:06,451
You know,

570
00:54:07,786 --> 00:54:10,079
I could do with some more beans.

571
00:54:10,164 --> 00:54:12,665
Go help yourself. There's more over there.

572
00:54:17,671 --> 00:54:19,255
It's too far.

573
00:54:22,635 --> 00:54:25,511
I wonder, when are we going back to the front ?

574
00:54:26,055 --> 00:54:27,055
Tomorrow.

575
00:54:30,976 --> 00:54:34,270
It's enough to take away a man's appetite.

576
00:54:34,855 --> 00:54:37,065
You know, if they're gonna march us in again tomorrow,

577
00:54:37,149 --> 00:54:38,650
we ought to go see how Kemmerick is.

578
00:54:38,734 --> 00:54:40,193
That's a good idea. Let's do that.

579
00:54:40,268 --> 00:54:41,588
How far is the dressing station ?

580
00:54:41,612 --> 00:54:43,071
About two miles.

581
00:54:43,739 --> 00:54:45,448
We could take his things to him.

582
00:54:45,532 --> 00:54:47,033
Good.

583
00:54:47,117 --> 00:54:50,787
It seemed rotten to think of a
thing like that happening to him,

584
00:54:50,871 --> 00:54:52,747
a nice fellow like Kemmerick.

585
00:54:52,831 --> 00:54:55,875
The French certainly deserve to
be punished for starting this war.

586
00:54:55,960 --> 00:54:58,044
Everybody says it's somebody else.

587
00:54:58,629 --> 00:55:01,214
Well, how do they start a war ?

588
00:55:01,298 --> 00:55:03,758
Well, one country offends another.

589
00:55:04,218 --> 00:55:06,594
How could one country offend another ?

590
00:55:06,679 --> 00:55:08,805
You mean, there's a mountain over in Germany

591
00:55:08,889 --> 00:55:10,807
gets mad at a field over in France ?

592
00:55:12,059 --> 00:55:15,186
Well, stupid, one people offends another.

593
00:55:15,896 --> 00:55:18,815
Oh, if that's it, I shouldn't be here at all.

594
00:55:18,899 --> 00:55:20,274
I don't feel offended.

595
00:55:21,902 --> 00:55:24,737
It don't apply to tramps like you.

596
00:55:25,155 --> 00:55:27,198
Good. Then I can be going home right away.

597
00:55:27,282 --> 00:55:28,282
You just try it.

598
00:55:28,367 --> 00:55:30,284
Yeah. You want to get shot ?

599
00:55:31,745 --> 00:55:32,996
The Kaiser and me...

600
00:55:35,916 --> 00:55:39,836
Me and the Kaiser felt just alike about this war.

601
00:55:39,920 --> 00:55:43,589
We didn't either of us want any war, so I'm going home.

602
00:55:43,674 --> 00:55:44,841
He's there already.

603
00:55:44,925 --> 00:55:48,261
Somebody must have wanted it. Maybe it was the English.

604
00:55:48,679 --> 00:55:51,556
No, I don't want to shoot any Englishmen.

605
00:55:51,640 --> 00:55:54,350
I never saw one till I came up here.

606
00:55:54,435 --> 00:55:56,602
And I suppose most of them never saw a German

607
00:55:56,687 --> 00:55:58,438
till they came up here.

608
00:55:58,522 --> 00:56:01,190
No, I'm sure they weren't asked about it.

609
00:56:01,275 --> 00:56:02,316
No.

610
00:56:02,985 --> 00:56:06,529
Well, it must be doing somebody some good.

611
00:56:07,031 --> 00:56:08,281
Not me and the Kaiser.

612
00:56:08,365 --> 00:56:10,950
I think maybe the Kaiser wanted a war.

613
00:56:11,952 --> 00:56:13,619
You leave us out of this.

614
00:56:16,290 --> 00:56:20,209
I don't see that. The Kaiser's got everything he needs.

615
00:56:20,544 --> 00:56:22,420
Well, he never had a war before.

616
00:56:22,504 --> 00:56:26,174
Every full-grown emperor needs one war to make him famous.

617
00:56:26,300 --> 00:56:27,383
Why, that's history.

618
00:56:27,468 --> 00:56:29,177
Yeah, Generals, too. They need war.

619
00:56:29,303 --> 00:56:31,512
And manufacturers. They get rich. Hmm.

620
00:56:31,597 --> 00:56:34,557
I think it's more a kind of fever.

621
00:56:34,641 --> 00:56:39,479
Nobody wants it in particular
and then, all at once, here it is.

622
00:56:39,897 --> 00:56:44,317
We didn't want it. The English
didn't want it. And here we are fighting.

623
00:56:44,735 --> 00:56:47,487
I'll tell you how it should all be done.

624
00:56:49,406 --> 00:56:51,783
Whenever there's a big war coming on,

625
00:56:51,867 --> 00:56:54,410
you should rope off a big field...

626
00:56:54,495 --> 00:56:55,578
And sell tickets.

627
00:56:55,662 --> 00:56:57,497
Yeah. And...

628
00:56:59,875 --> 00:57:01,501
And on the big day

629
00:57:01,585 --> 00:57:03,336
you should take all the kings

630
00:57:03,420 --> 00:57:06,380
and their cabinets and their Generals,

631
00:57:06,465 --> 00:57:08,674
put them in the center dressed in their underpants

632
00:57:08,759 --> 00:57:11,260
and let them fight it out with clubs.

633
00:57:11,345 --> 00:57:13,096
The best country wins.

634
00:57:15,224 --> 00:57:18,643
Well, now that Kat's settled
everything, let's go see Kemmerick.

635
00:57:18,727 --> 00:57:19,811
Might cheer him up.

636
00:57:19,895 --> 00:57:21,735
Something interesting might happen on the way.

637
00:57:21,759 --> 00:57:25,316
Boys, me and the Kaiser want
you back in time to march tomorrow.

638
00:57:25,400 --> 00:57:27,193
Don't forget.

639
00:57:27,277 --> 00:57:28,277
We'll be back.

640
00:57:28,362 --> 00:57:29,487
Give the boy my regards.

641
00:57:38,205 --> 00:57:39,288
Whoa.

642
00:57:50,884 --> 00:57:52,552
Oh, there he is.

643
00:57:54,221 --> 00:57:55,888
Hello, Kemmerick. How are you ?

644
00:57:55,973 --> 00:57:57,265
How's it going ?

645
00:57:57,349 --> 00:57:58,558
How are things going ?

646
00:57:58,642 --> 00:58:00,476
Are they looking after you all right ?

647
00:58:00,561 --> 00:58:02,937
How are they treating you ? Franz ?

648
00:58:03,897 --> 00:58:05,481
I'm all right.

649
00:58:06,984 --> 00:58:08,901
They're robbers here.

650
00:58:10,988 --> 00:58:12,238
Robbers.

651
00:58:14,783 --> 00:58:17,285
They stole my watch.

652
00:58:17,411 --> 00:58:20,121
I always told you nobody should
carry as good a watch as that.

653
00:58:20,247 --> 00:58:21,956
And they took it while I was under ether.

654
00:58:22,040 --> 00:58:24,208
Franz. Franz. You'll get it back.

655
00:58:25,586 --> 00:58:27,503
Do you feel all right ?

656
00:58:29,464 --> 00:58:31,424
Just look at my hand, though.

657
00:58:31,508 --> 00:58:33,301
That's because you lost so much blood.

658
00:58:33,385 --> 00:58:35,178
Just eat decently and you'll get well again.

659
00:58:35,262 --> 00:58:36,262
Oh, no.

660
00:58:36,346 --> 00:58:40,766
Franz, you must eat. That's
the main thing. It looks good, too.

661
00:58:44,771 --> 00:58:48,024
I have such a terrible pain in my foot.

662
00:58:49,985 --> 00:58:53,029
Every toe on my right foot hurts.

663
00:58:57,367 --> 00:59:00,453
Well, how can your foot hurt when your leg's been...

664
00:59:04,333 --> 00:59:06,125
Oh, I know what you mean !

665
00:59:06,835 --> 00:59:09,795
I know ! I know now !

666
00:59:12,090 --> 00:59:14,133
They've cut my leg off.

667
00:59:16,053 --> 00:59:20,806
Why didn't they tell me ?

668
00:59:20,891 --> 00:59:22,516
Franz ! Franz ! ...they tell me.

669
00:59:22,601 --> 00:59:24,060
Now I can't walk anymore !

670
00:59:24,144 --> 00:59:28,105
Franz, you must be thankful
that you've come off with only that.

671
00:59:33,820 --> 00:59:36,489
I wanted to be a forester once.

672
00:59:37,658 --> 00:59:41,452
You can yet. They make artificial legs that are wonderful.

673
00:59:42,329 --> 00:59:45,790
And you're through, too. You can go home. Think of that.

674
00:59:46,750 --> 00:59:49,335
We brought your things for you. See ?

675
00:59:50,003 --> 00:59:51,963
Put them under the bed.

676
00:59:59,680 --> 01:00:02,098
That's a marvelous pair of boots.

677
01:00:03,892 --> 01:00:05,726
Look at that leather.

678
01:00:05,811 --> 01:00:07,144
What comfort.

679
01:00:07,229 --> 01:00:09,188
I was just thinking.

680
01:00:12,359 --> 01:00:14,527
If you're not going to be using these, Franz,

681
01:00:14,611 --> 01:00:16,320
why don't you leave them with us ?

682
01:00:18,532 --> 01:00:22,159
What good are they to you ? I can use 'em.

683
01:00:22,244 --> 01:00:25,121
My boots give me blister after blister.

684
01:00:30,127 --> 01:00:32,253
Well, we'll be going, Franz.

685
01:00:32,337 --> 01:00:35,756
Oh, don't go. Stay just a little while longer.

686
01:00:37,426 --> 01:00:38,843
I'll come right back.

687
01:00:38,927 --> 01:00:40,553
We'll be coming soon again, Franz.

688
01:00:40,679 --> 01:00:42,596
I know you'll be feeling better, Franz. Bye.

689
01:00:42,681 --> 01:00:43,764
Bye.

690
01:00:43,849 --> 01:00:44,974
Goodbye, Franz.

691
01:00:45,392 --> 01:00:47,310
You think he'll last till after mess ?

692
01:00:47,394 --> 01:00:48,394
You don't think...

693
01:00:48,437 --> 01:00:49,603
Done for.

694
01:00:52,482 --> 01:00:54,608
Boys, you go along. I'll see you later.

695
01:00:54,735 --> 01:00:57,175
- Goodbye. All right, Paul.
- Goodbye, Paul.

696
01:01:00,407 --> 01:01:02,783
I'm sorry, Paul.

697
01:01:03,285 --> 01:01:06,620
I wouldn't touch a thing of his if he could use it.

698
01:01:06,913 --> 01:01:11,000
I'd go barefoot over barbed
wire for him if it'd do him any good.

699
01:01:11,084 --> 01:01:14,337
Only why should some orderly get those boots ?

700
01:01:14,421 --> 01:01:17,590
I understand, Mueller. We're all alike out here.

701
01:01:18,967 --> 01:01:20,968
And good boots are scarce.

702
01:01:29,144 --> 01:01:31,520
Tell the doctor to come, please.

703
01:01:38,528 --> 01:01:42,031
Doctor, the man in the next bed would like to see you, Sir.

704
01:01:42,115 --> 01:01:45,743
I've done everything I can for him. There's no helping him.

705
01:01:45,827 --> 01:01:47,536
Poor little fellow.

706
01:01:59,591 --> 01:02:01,634
He says next time, Franz.

707
01:02:11,645 --> 01:02:13,604
Do you think I'll ever get well ?

708
01:02:13,688 --> 01:02:15,606
Why, of course.

709
01:02:17,776 --> 01:02:19,902
Do you really think so ?

710
01:02:19,986 --> 01:02:22,488
Sure, once you get over the operation.

711
01:02:30,163 --> 01:02:31,997
I don't think so.

712
01:02:32,457 --> 01:02:36,502
Franz. Don't talk nonsense. Why, you'll be as good as new.

713
01:02:36,628 --> 01:02:39,338
They fix up worse things than that.

714
01:02:39,673 --> 01:02:42,466
Perhaps you'll go to the convalescent home in Klosterberg

715
01:02:42,551 --> 01:02:44,510
among the villagers.

716
01:02:45,470 --> 01:02:49,098
Then you can look out of the windows, across the field

717
01:02:49,182 --> 01:02:51,517
to the two trees on the horizon.

718
01:02:52,686 --> 01:02:56,313
The loveliest time of the year, now, when the corn ripens.

719
01:02:57,858 --> 01:03:00,359
And you can go out without asking anyone.

720
01:03:01,111 --> 01:03:03,779
You can even play piano if you want to.

721
01:03:07,993 --> 01:03:12,121
Oh... Oh, but, Franz, you must try to sleep now.

722
01:03:28,763 --> 01:03:30,055
Oh, God,

723
01:03:31,183 --> 01:03:35,728
this is Franz Kemmerick, only 19 years old.

724
01:03:37,272 --> 01:03:39,356
He doesn't want to die.

725
01:03:39,983 --> 01:03:42,234
Please, don't let him die.

726
01:03:43,069 --> 01:03:44,653
Paul.

727
01:03:44,738 --> 01:03:46,572
Paul. Yes, Franz.

728
01:03:48,700 --> 01:03:51,494
Take my boots home for Mueller.

729
01:03:51,578 --> 01:03:53,704
Oh, no, Franz, no.

730
01:03:54,623 --> 01:03:55,998
And if...

731
01:03:57,792 --> 01:04:00,252
Paul, you can find my watch,

732
01:04:01,880 --> 01:04:03,088
send it home.

733
01:04:03,173 --> 01:04:04,340
Franz !

734
01:04:07,761 --> 01:04:09,929
Doctor. Doctor !

735
01:04:10,931 --> 01:04:12,223
Doctor !

736
01:04:13,266 --> 01:04:15,768
Doctor ! Where's the doctor ?

737
01:04:15,977 --> 01:04:18,312
Why isn't there a doctor here ?

738
01:04:18,813 --> 01:04:21,190
Doctor, come quick. Franz Kemmerick is dying !

739
01:04:21,274 --> 01:04:22,816
Which one is that ? Amputated leg.

740
01:04:22,901 --> 01:04:24,360
I've amputated a dozen legs today.

741
01:04:24,444 --> 01:04:25,694
Bed 26, Sir.

742
01:04:25,779 --> 01:04:28,781
You see to it. I'm due in the operating room.

743
01:04:29,157 --> 01:04:32,493
One operation after another since 5:00 this morning.

744
01:04:32,577 --> 01:04:35,663
Sixteen dead today, yours is the 17th.

745
01:04:35,747 --> 01:04:38,457
There'll probably be 20 by tomorrow.

746
01:05:00,313 --> 01:05:02,982
You're looking good, very good today.

747
01:05:17,497 --> 01:05:18,497
What's your hurry ?

748
01:05:18,582 --> 01:05:20,082
Hey ! I'll bet he stole those boots !

749
01:05:20,166 --> 01:05:22,334
Why didn't you stop him ?

750
01:05:26,965 --> 01:05:28,132
I got it, Kat.

751
01:05:28,216 --> 01:05:29,216
Huh ?

752
01:05:29,676 --> 01:05:32,511
Listen, "The sum of an arithmetic series

753
01:05:32,637 --> 01:05:37,474
"is S = A + L x N over 2." Interesting, isn't it ?

754
01:05:37,559 --> 01:05:39,768
What do you want to learn that stuff for ?

755
01:05:39,853 --> 01:05:43,355
One day you'll stop a bullet and it'll all be wasted.

756
01:05:43,481 --> 01:05:45,649
I get a lot of fun out of it.

757
01:06:05,128 --> 01:06:07,046
My boots !

758
01:06:12,636 --> 01:06:14,136
Mueller.

759
01:06:15,764 --> 01:06:17,306
I saw him die.

760
01:06:21,311 --> 01:06:24,396
I didn't know what it was like to die before.

761
01:06:26,066 --> 01:06:30,319
And then... Then I came outside and it felt...

762
01:06:32,322 --> 01:06:37,326
It felt so good to be alive that I started in to walk fast.

763
01:06:38,119 --> 01:06:40,996
I began to think of the strangest things,

764
01:06:41,831 --> 01:06:45,167
like being out in the fields. Things like that.

765
01:06:46,795 --> 01:06:49,171
You know, girls.

766
01:06:51,091 --> 01:06:53,592
And it felt as if there were

767
01:06:53,677 --> 01:06:57,388
something electric running from the ground up through me.

768
01:06:57,472 --> 01:07:00,349
And I started. And I began to run hard.

769
01:07:00,433 --> 01:07:03,102
And I passed soldiers and I heard voices calling, but...

770
01:07:03,186 --> 01:07:05,104
And I ran and I ran.

771
01:07:05,522 --> 01:07:09,108
And I felt as if I couldn't breathe enough air into me.

772
01:07:11,653 --> 01:07:14,613
And... And now I'm hungry.

773
01:07:19,369 --> 01:07:21,161
I don't mind the war now.

774
01:07:21,287 --> 01:07:24,623
Be a pleasure to go to the front in boots like these.

775
01:08:16,509 --> 01:08:18,427
It's a good invention, just the same.

776
01:08:18,502 --> 01:08:19,822
If you crack each separate louse,

777
01:08:19,846 --> 01:08:22,890
think of all the energy you use up. Watch.

778
01:08:25,810 --> 01:08:27,478
Burned to death.

779
01:08:29,189 --> 01:08:30,689
How was patrol ? Bad ?

780
01:08:30,774 --> 01:08:33,859
Must've been terrible if they
had time to gather in the harvest.

781
01:08:33,943 --> 01:08:36,543
We passed a cherry tree and
when he saw it, he sort of went crazy.

782
01:08:36,571 --> 01:08:38,489
I could hardly drag him away.

783
01:08:38,990 --> 01:08:40,991
It was beautiful.

784
01:08:43,203 --> 01:08:46,288
I have a big orchard with cherry trees at home.

785
01:08:47,832 --> 01:08:50,167
And when they're in full blossom,

786
01:08:50,251 --> 01:08:53,337
from the hayloft it looks like one single sheet.

787
01:08:54,214 --> 01:08:55,506
So white.

788
01:08:57,967 --> 01:08:59,426
Perhaps you can get leave soon.

789
01:08:59,511 --> 01:09:02,346
You may even be sent back as a farmer.

790
01:09:02,722 --> 01:09:06,350
A woman can't run a farm alone. That's no good, you know ?

791
01:09:06,434 --> 01:09:08,644
No matter how hard she works.

792
01:09:10,021 --> 01:09:12,022
Harvest coming on again.

793
01:09:14,609 --> 01:09:15,859
What's the matter with him ?

794
01:09:15,944 --> 01:09:17,569
Got a letter yesterday from his wife.

795
01:09:17,737 --> 01:09:19,404
He wants to get back to his farm.

796
01:09:19,531 --> 01:09:22,115
We'd all like to get back home, it comes to that.

797
01:09:22,200 --> 01:09:24,868
I wonder what we'd do if it were suddenly peacetime again ?

798
01:09:24,953 --> 01:09:27,162
Get drunk and look for women !

799
01:09:27,705 --> 01:09:29,790
I'd go looking for a Cinderella

800
01:09:29,874 --> 01:09:31,917
that could wear this for a garter.

801
01:09:32,669 --> 01:09:35,879
And when I'd found her, nobody would see me for two weeks.

802
01:09:37,215 --> 01:09:39,550
I'll go back to the peat fields

803
01:09:40,593 --> 01:09:43,554
and those pleasant hours in the beer gardens.

804
01:09:44,764 --> 01:09:47,766
And there's worse things than cobbling, too.

805
01:09:48,309 --> 01:09:50,102
Look. My family.

806
01:09:53,731 --> 01:09:56,942
I ought to give you a kick in
the backside for starting all this.

807
01:09:57,026 --> 01:09:58,569
It's all right for all you to talk.

808
01:09:58,653 --> 01:10:00,487
You've got something to go back to.

809
01:10:00,572 --> 01:10:02,573
Wives, children, jobs...

810
01:10:03,616 --> 01:10:07,494
But what about us ? What have
we got to go back to ? School ?

811
01:10:07,579 --> 01:10:09,872
Why not ? You know everything already ?

812
01:10:09,956 --> 01:10:13,417
A man can't take all that rubbish they teach you seriously

813
01:10:13,501 --> 01:10:16,962
after three years of shells and bombs.

814
01:10:17,422 --> 01:10:19,673
You can't peel that off as easily as a sock.

815
01:10:19,757 --> 01:10:21,842
They never taught us anything really useful,

816
01:10:21,926 --> 01:10:23,606
like how to light a cigarette in the wind,

817
01:10:23,678 --> 01:10:25,804
or make a fire out of wet wood,

818
01:10:25,889 --> 01:10:29,725
or bayonet a man in the belly instead
of the ribs where it gets jammed.

819
01:10:29,851 --> 01:10:32,185
What can happen to us afterwards ?

820
01:10:32,270 --> 01:10:34,479
I'll tell you. Take our class.

821
01:10:35,315 --> 01:10:38,150
Out of 20, three are officers,

822
01:10:38,985 --> 01:10:40,402
nine dead,

823
01:10:41,279 --> 01:10:44,990
Mueller and three others wounded, and one in the madhouse.

824
01:10:45,992 --> 01:10:48,994
We'll all be dead someday, so let's forget it.

825
01:10:51,581 --> 01:10:54,333
Hurry up ! Get in there ! Hurry up !

826
01:10:56,502 --> 01:10:57,836
Himmelstoss !

827
01:11:05,678 --> 01:11:07,012
What's up ?

828
01:11:07,347 --> 01:11:08,430
What are you, crazy ?

829
01:11:08,514 --> 01:11:09,848
It's Himmelstoss !

830
01:11:09,933 --> 01:11:12,809
Himmelstoss ? There is justice in the army !

831
01:11:15,855 --> 01:11:19,441
Well, well. So, we are all here, huh ?

832
01:11:19,525 --> 01:11:21,401
A bit longer than you, Himmie.

833
01:11:21,486 --> 01:11:23,987
And since when have we become so familiar ?

834
01:11:24,072 --> 01:11:26,531
Stand up there and click your heels together ! All of you !

835
01:11:26,616 --> 01:11:29,034
Take a running jump at yourself !

836
01:11:29,118 --> 01:11:30,494
Who's your friend ?

837
01:11:30,578 --> 01:11:34,373
Would somebody get General
Ludendorff a nice, comfortable chair ?

838
01:11:35,583 --> 01:11:37,668
I command you as your superior officer !

839
01:11:37,752 --> 01:11:39,512
Do you want to be court-martialed for this ?

840
01:11:39,536 --> 01:11:39,962
I do !

841
01:11:40,046 --> 01:11:41,646
There's going to be a big attack tonight

842
01:11:41,670 --> 01:11:43,296
and I'd just love to get out of it.

843
01:11:44,425 --> 01:11:46,218
Will you obey my orders ?

844
01:11:46,386 --> 01:11:48,178
Kiss my foot.

845
01:11:53,851 --> 01:11:56,770
It isn't customary to ask for salutes here.

846
01:11:56,854 --> 01:11:58,397
But I'll tell you what we'll do.

847
01:11:58,481 --> 01:12:01,191
We're going to attack a town
that we tried to take once before.

848
01:12:01,275 --> 01:12:04,319
Many killed and many wounded. It was great fun.

849
01:12:04,487 --> 01:12:06,822
This time you're going with us.

850
01:12:06,906 --> 01:12:09,491
If any of us stops a bullet, before we die,

851
01:12:09,575 --> 01:12:12,327
we're going to come to you, click
our heels together and ask stiffly,

852
01:12:12,412 --> 01:12:14,705
"Please, Sergeant Himmelstoss, may we go ?"

853
01:12:14,831 --> 01:12:17,874
You'll... You'll pay for this, you...

854
01:12:24,966 --> 01:12:26,341
Here it is.

855
01:12:29,512 --> 01:12:32,180
Right on time. Better get ready, boys.

856
01:13:30,865 --> 01:13:32,824
I'm wounded. I'm wounded !

857
01:13:32,909 --> 01:13:37,120
It's just a scratch, you yellow
rat ! Up ! Get on with the others ! Up !

858
01:13:37,705 --> 01:13:39,372
No ! No ! No !

859
01:13:39,749 --> 01:13:41,291
You yellow rat !

860
01:13:41,584 --> 01:13:45,629
You stinking yellow rat ! Let the others do it, eh ?

861
01:13:45,713 --> 01:13:47,297
Get up ! Get up !

862
01:13:48,508 --> 01:13:51,968
Forward, forward ! Get out here !

863
01:13:52,261 --> 01:13:54,596
The command was forward.

864
01:13:58,351 --> 01:14:00,102
Command was forward !

865
01:14:00,770 --> 01:14:01,978
Forward !

866
01:14:04,023 --> 01:14:06,399
Forward ! Forward !

867
01:14:08,820 --> 01:14:13,532
Forward !

868
01:15:55,259 --> 01:15:56,551
Counterattack.

869
01:18:32,166 --> 01:18:36,753
I want to help you.

870
01:19:30,766 --> 01:19:33,059
Stop that ! Stop that !

871
01:19:34,687 --> 01:19:37,856
I can bear the rest of it. I can't listen to that !

872
01:19:46,782 --> 01:19:48,366
Why do you take so long dying ?

873
01:19:48,451 --> 01:19:50,410
You're going to die anyway !

874
01:19:55,416 --> 01:19:58,751
Oh, no. Oh, no. You won't die.

875
01:19:59,253 --> 01:20:02,464
No, no. You won't die. They're only little wounds.

876
01:20:03,591 --> 01:20:05,884
You'll get home. You'll be all right.

877
01:20:07,052 --> 01:20:09,554
You'll get home long before I will.

878
01:21:12,034 --> 01:21:14,953
You know I can't run away. That's why you accuse me.

879
01:21:16,455 --> 01:21:19,999
I tell you, I didn't want to kill
you. I tried to keep you alive.

880
01:21:20,960 --> 01:21:24,254
If you jumped in here again, I wouldn't do it.

881
01:21:24,338 --> 01:21:26,714
You see when you jumped in here you were my enemy,

882
01:21:26,799 --> 01:21:28,132
and I was afraid of you.

883
01:21:29,843 --> 01:21:32,845
But you're just a man like me, and I killed you.

884
01:21:34,348 --> 01:21:36,474
Forgive me, comrade.

885
01:21:37,393 --> 01:21:39,602
Say that for me. Say you forgive me.

886
01:21:41,522 --> 01:21:43,439
Oh, no. You're dead.

887
01:21:45,109 --> 01:21:48,903
Only, you're better off than I am. You're through.

888
01:21:48,988 --> 01:21:51,281
They can't do anymore to you now.

889
01:21:52,825 --> 01:21:56,035
Oh, God, why did they do this to us ?

890
01:21:56,495 --> 01:21:58,705
We only wanted to live, you and I.

891
01:21:59,707 --> 01:22:03,167
Why should they send us out to fight each other ?

892
01:22:03,252 --> 01:22:05,587
If we threw away these rifles and these uniforms

893
01:22:05,671 --> 01:22:08,548
you could be my brother, just like Kat and Albert.

894
01:22:09,925 --> 01:22:13,261
You'll have to forgive me, comrade. I'll do all I can.

895
01:22:13,887 --> 01:22:16,889
I'll write to your parents. I'll write to...

896
01:22:43,709 --> 01:22:46,669
I'll write to your wife. I'll write to her.

897
01:22:48,213 --> 01:22:51,215
I promise she'll not want for anything.

898
01:22:51,884 --> 01:22:54,469
And I'll help her and your parents, too.

899
01:22:54,553 --> 01:22:58,306
Only, forgive me. Forgive me !

900
01:22:58,390 --> 01:23:01,017
Forgive me. Forgive me.

901
01:23:01,977 --> 01:23:03,895
Forgive me.

902
01:23:48,482 --> 01:23:51,109
Terrible thing happened yesterday.

903
01:23:51,235 --> 01:23:54,570
I stabbed a man. With my own hands, stabbed him.

904
01:23:54,655 --> 01:23:58,783
I know how it is. Your first time.

905
01:23:59,284 --> 01:24:01,661
Never mind. The stretcher-bearers will find him.

906
01:24:01,787 --> 01:24:03,871
No, no. He's dead, Kat. I watched him die.

907
01:24:03,956 --> 01:24:05,957
You couldn't do anything about it.

908
01:24:06,083 --> 01:24:09,335
We have to kill. We can't help it.

909
01:24:09,461 --> 01:24:13,673
That's what we are here for. Look there, for instance.

910
01:24:15,968 --> 01:24:19,679
That got him. You should've seen how he leaped in the air.

911
01:24:20,848 --> 01:24:24,308
That fellow headed the shoot
with us for today with three hits.

912
01:24:24,393 --> 01:24:26,477
If he keeps it up, he'll have a decoration

913
01:24:26,562 --> 01:24:28,980
for his buttonhole this evening.

914
01:24:29,356 --> 01:24:32,775
Now, don't you lose anymore sleep over this business.

915
01:24:32,860 --> 01:24:35,570
Maybe it was 'cause I was out there with him so long, huh ?

916
01:24:35,654 --> 01:24:37,530
Sure, that's it.

917
01:24:39,199 --> 01:24:41,200
After all, war is war.

918
01:25:18,447 --> 01:25:19,781
March !

919
01:25:19,865 --> 01:25:21,949
Forward, march !

920
01:25:34,505 --> 01:25:36,923
Quickly ! Forward !

921
01:25:38,467 --> 01:25:40,551
Company, halt !

922
01:25:42,054 --> 01:25:43,429
Dismissed !

923
01:25:45,516 --> 01:25:48,893
Noncommissioned officers, enlisted men, dismissed !

924
01:25:50,562 --> 01:25:53,189
Hooray ! Come on, let's get out of here !

925
01:26:21,468 --> 01:26:22,508
Give me your best sausage.

926
01:26:22,553 --> 01:26:23,594
Two.

927
01:26:25,639 --> 01:26:27,181
Give me a beer.

928
01:26:35,357 --> 01:26:37,441
One, two, three, hoorah !

929
01:26:43,615 --> 01:26:46,158
Hey, come on. A beer.

930
01:26:48,620 --> 01:26:50,705
Hey, get out of here !

931
01:26:50,789 --> 01:26:52,832
Come on. Give me a beer.

932
01:26:57,212 --> 01:26:59,380
A beer. One...

933
01:27:00,632 --> 01:27:01,966
Prosit !

934
01:27:05,137 --> 01:27:08,639
Well, here's hoping we get falling-down drunk tonight.

935
01:27:08,724 --> 01:27:10,725
Here's how it started.

936
01:27:26,366 --> 01:27:28,910
I'd forgotten there were girls like that.

937
01:27:28,994 --> 01:27:30,620
There aren't.

938
01:27:32,080 --> 01:27:34,415
Just look at those thin, little shoes.

939
01:27:34,917 --> 01:27:37,251
She couldn't march many miles in those.

940
01:27:37,753 --> 01:27:40,630
Paul. Don't speak about marching.

941
01:27:40,714 --> 01:27:42,548
You're boring the young lady.

942
01:27:44,593 --> 01:27:46,510
A thousand pardons.

943
01:27:48,680 --> 01:27:50,598
How old do you think she is ?

944
01:27:50,682 --> 01:27:54,143
Oh, about 22.

945
01:27:54,227 --> 01:27:56,729
No, you know, that'd make her older than us.

946
01:27:56,813 --> 01:28:00,191
She's 17.

947
01:28:03,946 --> 01:28:08,074
A girl like that. That'd be good, eh, Albert ?

948
01:28:13,205 --> 01:28:16,457
We wouldn't have much of a chance with him around.

949
01:28:31,890 --> 01:28:34,475
We could take a bath, wash our clothes...

950
01:28:34,559 --> 01:28:36,060
All right.

951
01:28:36,144 --> 01:28:38,938
I might even go so far as to get deloused.

952
01:28:39,022 --> 01:28:40,648
Wait a minute ! Wait a minute !

953
01:28:40,732 --> 01:28:42,733
She's a long way from here now.

954
01:28:42,818 --> 01:28:45,528
Look at the date. May 1917.

955
01:28:45,612 --> 01:28:47,196
Four months ago.

956
01:28:47,280 --> 01:28:49,073
That's true.

957
01:28:49,157 --> 01:28:51,993
Well, here's to her anyway.

958
01:28:52,536 --> 01:28:55,371
Here's to 'em all, everywhere.

959
01:28:59,501 --> 01:29:03,462
Albert, we might as well wash up anyway.

960
01:29:03,547 --> 01:29:04,630
All right.

961
01:29:08,010 --> 01:29:11,512
Personally, I like them bigger around.

962
01:29:11,596 --> 01:29:14,432
This conversation was on a high moral plane up to now.

963
01:29:14,516 --> 01:29:16,976
Now we do need a bath.

964
01:29:17,269 --> 01:29:19,228
A bath ? For what ?

965
01:29:21,481 --> 01:29:23,566
You wouldn't understand.

966
01:29:29,406 --> 01:29:32,324
This water's freezing. This
romantic business has gone too far.

967
01:29:32,409 --> 01:29:34,994
But think of her beautiful eyes !

968
01:29:35,078 --> 01:29:37,621
Oh, and her hair.

969
01:29:37,706 --> 01:29:39,466
Here we are ! We're not gonna miss a thing !

970
01:29:39,490 --> 01:29:40,207
Go away !

971
01:29:40,292 --> 01:29:41,292
What are you doing here ?

972
01:29:41,334 --> 01:29:42,376
Bathing !

973
01:29:42,461 --> 01:29:44,712
They tell me there's some people in this world

974
01:29:44,796 --> 01:29:46,922
takes a bath every week !

975
01:29:48,091 --> 01:29:49,633
Women !

976
01:30:04,441 --> 01:30:06,442
Mademoiselle, you want to swim ?

977
01:30:21,666 --> 01:30:23,542
Mademoiselle, you could be me !

978
01:30:35,305 --> 01:30:37,181
Oh, baby !

979
01:30:38,308 --> 01:30:39,350
Kiss me !

980
01:30:45,148 --> 01:30:47,566
No, girls ! Don't go away !

981
01:30:51,029 --> 01:30:52,822
Oh, mama !

982
01:31:00,789 --> 01:31:02,289
Please don't go !

983
01:31:02,374 --> 01:31:03,874
Don't go away !

984
01:31:04,334 --> 01:31:05,876
Mademoiselle, we want you.

985
01:31:15,345 --> 01:31:17,930
Food ! Food ! Whoo !

986
01:31:41,079 --> 01:31:42,121
Halt !

987
01:31:42,205 --> 01:31:44,206
You know you're forbidden to cross.

988
01:31:44,291 --> 01:31:48,544
You fellows stay on this side or
you'll get yourselves in a lot of trouble.

989
01:32:01,808 --> 01:32:03,350
What are they jabbering about ?

990
01:32:03,435 --> 01:32:05,716
They want us to swing over tonight. They're expecting us.

991
01:32:05,740 --> 01:32:06,937
That's fine ! We'll do it !

992
01:32:07,022 --> 01:32:08,564
That blonde's crazy about me.

993
01:32:08,648 --> 01:32:10,900
But there's four of us and only three of them.

994
01:32:10,984 --> 01:32:12,693
I was the one that stopped 'em !

995
01:32:12,777 --> 01:32:14,486
That blonde piece of work is mine.

996
01:32:14,571 --> 01:32:16,530
You three fight for what's left.

997
01:32:16,615 --> 01:32:20,409
Fight's the word. All's fair in love and war.

998
01:32:20,493 --> 01:32:22,953
Huh ? What do you mean ? What are you gonna do ?

999
01:32:23,038 --> 01:32:24,663
You'll find out.

1000
01:32:55,654 --> 01:32:57,613
She means the door.

1001
01:33:21,179 --> 01:33:22,490
Not only modest, but dashing !

1002
01:33:22,514 --> 01:33:23,764
A perfect fit.

1003
01:33:23,848 --> 01:33:25,008
It might've been made for me.

1004
01:33:25,032 --> 01:33:28,075
An officer's coat. We're calling, distinguished company.

1005
01:34:39,174 --> 01:34:41,717
Have another little drink, comrade.

1006
01:34:43,762 --> 01:34:47,264
Is this your birthday or mine ?

1007
01:34:47,557 --> 01:34:48,849
Why ?

1008
01:34:49,601 --> 01:34:53,854
You've been buying me drink after drink for two hours.

1009
01:34:53,938 --> 01:34:58,359
What I'm trying to figure out is why.

1010
01:34:58,777 --> 01:35:02,196
Why ? Why ?

1011
01:35:03,948 --> 01:35:06,450
Oh !

1012
01:35:08,286 --> 01:35:11,872
It's just that the boys

1013
01:35:11,956 --> 01:35:16,418
told me to amuse you for a little while.

1014
01:35:17,087 --> 01:35:19,546
Oh, nice boys.

1015
01:35:19,631 --> 01:35:21,048
Yeah !

1016
01:35:21,132 --> 01:35:24,635
Yeah, they said you'd understand.

1017
01:35:32,936 --> 01:35:34,895
I've been betrayed !

1018
01:35:34,979 --> 01:35:37,940
Yeah, you certainly have.

1019
01:35:38,024 --> 01:35:40,692
Take that for a minute !

1020
01:35:40,819 --> 01:35:42,653
I'll give you more !

1021
01:35:53,665 --> 01:35:56,208
It's too loud.

1022
01:36:29,200 --> 01:36:30,492
Darling.

1023
01:36:31,202 --> 01:36:32,953
What's your name ?

1024
01:36:35,165 --> 01:36:37,749
Name. How do you say name ?

1025
01:36:38,334 --> 01:36:40,836
Georgette ? Camille ?

1026
01:36:43,548 --> 01:36:46,383
Suzanne.

1027
01:36:49,721 --> 01:36:51,763
Paul.

1028
01:36:54,517 --> 01:36:58,604
Suzanne, I wish I could tell you something.

1029
01:36:59,105 --> 01:37:00,939
I wish you could understand.

1030
01:37:02,233 --> 01:37:07,362
Darling, I'll never see you again. I know that.

1031
01:37:08,406 --> 01:37:10,407
And I wouldn't even know you if I did.

1032
01:37:10,533 --> 01:37:15,245
And yet, I'll remember you always.

1033
01:37:18,917 --> 01:37:21,001
If you could only know how different this is

1034
01:37:21,085 --> 01:37:23,212
from the women that we soldiers meet.

1035
01:37:27,550 --> 01:37:30,802
No, no, no. Not the war.

1036
01:37:30,929 --> 01:37:33,764
You. That's what I'm talking about.

1037
01:37:37,060 --> 01:37:41,396
It seems as though all war, terror and grossness

1038
01:37:41,481 --> 01:37:45,192
had fallen away from me, like a miracle.

1039
01:37:46,778 --> 01:37:48,820
Like something I never believed.

1040
01:37:57,497 --> 01:37:59,164
Call Paul.

1041
01:38:00,375 --> 01:38:02,125
We're going, Paul.

1042
01:38:32,657 --> 01:38:35,033
Have a look. Nice, new coffins.

1043
01:38:35,118 --> 01:38:36,451
For us.

1044
01:38:37,870 --> 01:38:39,454
I must say, that's a very cheerful

1045
01:38:39,539 --> 01:38:41,081
preparation for this offensive.

1046
01:38:41,165 --> 01:38:42,916
That's very considerate of them.

1047
01:38:43,001 --> 01:38:46,587
But I don't see any long enough for our comrade, Tjaden.

1048
01:38:46,671 --> 01:38:49,590
Mind you, I'm not speaking to you, you traitors.

1049
01:38:49,674 --> 01:38:52,217
But no coffin's gonna get me.

1050
01:38:52,302 --> 01:38:55,304
I should say not, heartbreaker.

1051
01:38:55,388 --> 01:38:58,265
You'll be thankful if they slip a waterproof sheet

1052
01:38:58,349 --> 01:39:01,685
around that Aunt Sally of a carcass of yours.

1053
01:39:31,507 --> 01:39:33,717
My side !

1054
01:39:38,389 --> 01:39:39,640
My side.

1055
01:39:57,867 --> 01:39:59,701
Catholic hospital, Albert.

1056
01:40:01,329 --> 01:40:04,748
They say you always get good food and good treatment.

1057
01:40:04,957 --> 01:40:06,083
We're lucky.

1058
01:40:06,167 --> 01:40:07,626
After that rainy dressing station

1059
01:40:07,710 --> 01:40:10,504
and 24 hours on the train, we deserve to have some luck.

1060
01:40:16,552 --> 01:40:18,095
I'm Hammacher.

1061
01:40:21,391 --> 01:40:23,684
Yes, that's my name.

1062
01:40:24,394 --> 01:40:27,688
I got a crack in the head and
they gave me a certificate stating

1063
01:40:27,772 --> 01:40:30,482
that Joseph Hammacher is periodically

1064
01:40:30,566 --> 01:40:33,235
not responsible for his actions.

1065
01:40:34,904 --> 01:40:40,200
And ever since then, Hammacher has been having a grand time.

1066
01:40:49,085 --> 01:40:52,379
I hope you boys are not too badly wounded.

1067
01:40:53,423 --> 01:40:58,427
The others die off so quickly we
don't have time to get acquainted.

1068
01:40:58,803 --> 01:41:01,722
You'll get to know us very well.

1069
01:41:03,141 --> 01:41:05,976
Thank you. You, too.

1070
01:41:11,399 --> 01:41:15,527
I'm sorry, my dear. It's time to go now.

1071
01:41:16,362 --> 01:41:18,238
Yes, Sister.

1072
01:41:25,621 --> 01:41:27,330
Watch.

1073
01:41:29,459 --> 01:41:33,253
If they take his clothes away, you've seen the last of him.

1074
01:41:34,630 --> 01:41:37,132
See ? They're taking him to the dying room.

1075
01:41:37,216 --> 01:41:38,550
Dying room ?

1076
01:41:38,634 --> 01:41:40,114
When you're ready to kick the bucket,

1077
01:41:40,138 --> 01:41:43,263
they get you out of the way so they can use the bed.

1078
01:41:43,347 --> 01:41:44,723
In the corner of the building

1079
01:41:44,807 --> 01:41:48,852
there's a little room right next to the morgue !

1080
01:41:50,062 --> 01:41:52,814
It's so convenient. It saves a lot of trouble.

1081
01:41:52,899 --> 01:41:54,983
But suppose he gets well ?

1082
01:41:55,067 --> 01:41:57,819
I've seen a lot of them go in that dying room,

1083
01:41:57,904 --> 01:42:00,989
but nobody ever comes back.

1084
01:42:27,350 --> 01:42:31,019
Sister. Sister. Sister.

1085
01:42:33,856 --> 01:42:34,898
Sister.

1086
01:42:43,908 --> 01:42:45,177
Is that you ringing, Paul ?

1087
01:42:45,201 --> 01:42:46,409
Yes.

1088
01:42:47,161 --> 01:42:48,662
Is something wrong ?

1089
01:42:48,746 --> 01:42:50,163
I think I have a hemorrhage.

1090
01:42:50,248 --> 01:42:54,292
The bandage is all wet. I've been
ringing forever and nobody comes.

1091
01:42:56,087 --> 01:42:57,337
I think I'm bleeding.

1092
01:42:57,421 --> 01:42:59,714
Sister, get me a sterile dressing and an ice pack.

1093
01:42:59,799 --> 01:43:00,966
Why didn't someone call me ?

1094
01:43:01,050 --> 01:43:02,509
He's been ringing.

1095
01:43:02,593 --> 01:43:04,803
Nobody can walk, Sister.

1096
01:43:04,887 --> 01:43:06,346
Sister, is it bad ?

1097
01:43:06,430 --> 01:43:08,849
No. No, we'll be all right.

1098
01:43:08,933 --> 01:43:10,433
We've got it in time.

1099
01:43:58,900 --> 01:44:01,610
What's the matter ? What are you doing ?

1100
01:44:01,694 --> 01:44:03,987
We must rearrange your bandages.

1101
01:44:05,740 --> 01:44:08,074
Where are you taking me ?

1102
01:44:08,159 --> 01:44:09,993
To the bandaging ward.

1103
01:44:17,919 --> 01:44:20,837
No, no ! I'm not going ! I'm staying here !

1104
01:44:20,922 --> 01:44:22,047
Paul ! Paul !

1105
01:44:22,131 --> 01:44:23,256
Now, now !

1106
01:44:23,341 --> 01:44:24,484
I'm not going to the dying room !

1107
01:44:24,508 --> 01:44:26,028
But we're going to the bandaging ward.

1108
01:44:26,052 --> 01:44:27,492
Then why are you taking my clothes ?

1109
01:44:27,553 --> 01:44:31,348
You're lying to me ! But I'll come back ! I won't die !

1110
01:44:31,432 --> 01:44:37,103
I'll come back ! I won't die !

1111
01:44:37,188 --> 01:44:39,981
I'm not going to die ! I'll come back !

1112
01:44:50,534 --> 01:44:52,619
Sister Libertine, how is he ?

1113
01:44:52,703 --> 01:44:56,122
Poor boy. They had to amputate his leg.

1114
01:45:11,305 --> 01:45:12,389
Paul.

1115
01:45:13,474 --> 01:45:18,228
Paul. Paul.

1116
01:45:19,355 --> 01:45:22,983
Oh, he is gone.

1117
01:45:23,985 --> 01:45:25,151
Gone.

1118
01:45:30,241 --> 01:45:34,244
Hello. Welcome home, Albert !

1119
01:45:36,706 --> 01:45:37,998
How do you feel, kid ?

1120
01:45:38,082 --> 01:45:39,332
All right.

1121
01:45:39,417 --> 01:45:42,252
But I've got such an awful pain.

1122
01:45:42,586 --> 01:45:44,504
My foot...

1123
01:45:48,884 --> 01:45:52,345
Hammacher. Did they cut my leg off ?

1124
01:45:52,430 --> 01:45:55,682
Of course not ! How many did you have ? Two ?

1125
01:45:55,766 --> 01:45:58,560
You still got 'em ! One, two !

1126
01:45:58,936 --> 01:46:02,897
Don't play the fool, Hammacher. Tell me truthfully.

1127
01:46:02,982 --> 01:46:06,234
Of course not. And you look fine.

1128
01:46:08,904 --> 01:46:11,448
Look. See ?

1129
01:46:25,421 --> 01:46:27,005
I won't be a cripple. Now, now.

1130
01:46:27,131 --> 01:46:28,965
I won't live like that ! Be calm.

1131
01:46:29,091 --> 01:46:30,800
I'll kill myself the first chance I get !

1132
01:46:30,885 --> 01:46:31,885
Albert !

1133
01:46:31,969 --> 01:46:35,180
I won't live ! I won't live ! Yes, you will.

1134
01:46:35,306 --> 01:46:37,766
Albert ! Albert !

1135
01:46:38,684 --> 01:46:40,769
Albert, I've come back !

1136
01:46:40,853 --> 01:46:44,689
I told you I'd come back. Look, everybody ! I've come back !

1137
01:46:44,815 --> 01:46:45,815
Paul ! Paul !

1138
01:46:45,941 --> 01:46:48,068
That's not where I'm going. I live over there.

1139
01:46:48,152 --> 01:46:50,153
Paul, I'm so happy.

1140
01:46:50,946 --> 01:46:52,947
Hammacher, I've come back from the dead !

1141
01:46:53,032 --> 01:46:55,742
It's most irregular. Never happened before.

1142
01:46:55,826 --> 01:46:58,912
Albert, we must get well quickly so we can go home soon.

1143
01:46:58,996 --> 01:47:00,830
Albert, everything will be all right now.

1144
01:47:00,956 --> 01:47:04,959
Yes, Paul. Everything will be all right now.

1145
01:48:37,469 --> 01:48:40,847
Paul ! Paul ! Paul !

1146
01:48:42,266 --> 01:48:43,349
Paul.

1147
01:48:44,810 --> 01:48:46,853
What's the matter, Paul ?

1148
01:48:46,937 --> 01:48:49,314
Nothing. Nothing.

1149
01:49:11,962 --> 01:49:13,463
Paul.

1150
01:49:13,881 --> 01:49:15,632
Give me your handkerchief.

1151
01:49:25,142 --> 01:49:26,226
Mother ?

1152
01:49:26,310 --> 01:49:28,978
Here I am, Paul. Here I am.

1153
01:49:32,316 --> 01:49:33,983
Mother's ill.

1154
01:49:51,252 --> 01:49:52,585
Are you wounded ?

1155
01:49:52,670 --> 01:49:54,587
No, Mother. I got leave.

1156
01:50:02,763 --> 01:50:06,432
Here I lie and cry instead of being glad.

1157
01:50:07,768 --> 01:50:11,604
Anna, get down the jar of blackberries.

1158
01:50:12,439 --> 01:50:15,275
You still like them, don't you ?

1159
01:50:15,359 --> 01:50:18,695
Yes, Mother. I haven't had any for a long time.

1160
01:50:21,949 --> 01:50:24,450
We might almost have known you were coming.

1161
01:50:25,035 --> 01:50:26,786
I'm making potato cakes.

1162
01:50:26,912 --> 01:50:28,663
Don't let them burn.

1163
01:50:30,124 --> 01:50:34,627
Paul, sit down beside me.

1164
01:50:39,800 --> 01:50:41,634
My Paul.

1165
01:50:43,762 --> 01:50:45,638
My baby.

1166
01:50:48,142 --> 01:50:52,061
I almost forgot, Mother. I've
got some little presents for you.

1167
01:51:07,703 --> 01:51:11,331
Look, Mother. Bread, sausage and rice.

1168
01:51:11,415 --> 01:51:14,500
Paul, you've been starving yourself.

1169
01:51:14,835 --> 01:51:17,962
Hadn't I better go and tell Father Paul's home ?

1170
01:51:18,047 --> 01:51:19,839
Paul could watch the things on the stove.

1171
01:51:19,923 --> 01:51:22,842
No, no, child, I'm getting up.

1172
01:51:22,926 --> 01:51:26,721
Oh, Paul, you're a soldier now, aren't you ?

1173
01:51:27,598 --> 01:51:31,017
But somehow, I don't seem to know you.

1174
01:51:32,102 --> 01:51:33,978
I'll take these off, Mother.

1175
01:51:34,063 --> 01:51:37,857
I'll get your suit, Paul. It's in the
wardrobe, just where you left it.

1176
01:51:37,941 --> 01:51:40,902
Are you really here, Paul ?

1177
01:51:40,986 --> 01:51:42,445
You won't...

1178
01:51:42,529 --> 01:51:45,948
You won't disappear, will you ?

1179
01:51:46,784 --> 01:51:49,369
No. I'm here.

1180
01:52:05,886 --> 01:52:08,471
Your things are ready for you, Paul.

1181
01:52:09,890 --> 01:52:11,330
I remember when you caught that one.

1182
01:52:11,392 --> 01:52:14,143
Yes. And you took it away from me, didn't you ?

1183
01:52:15,187 --> 01:52:16,979
Yes, I did.

1184
01:52:31,203 --> 01:52:32,870
We're behind the lines,

1185
01:52:32,955 --> 01:52:34,622
but we know how to honor the soldier

1186
01:52:34,706 --> 01:52:37,417
who goes on in spite of blood and death.

1187
01:52:37,501 --> 01:52:39,168
Gentlemen, my son.

1188
01:52:40,421 --> 01:52:42,088
Prosit. Prosit.

1189
01:52:46,260 --> 01:52:49,720
I'm glad to know you, young man, I am glad to know you.

1190
01:52:50,139 --> 01:52:54,267
And how are things out there ? Terrible, eh ? Terrible.

1191
01:52:55,477 --> 01:52:57,562
But we must carry on.

1192
01:52:58,230 --> 01:53:02,316
After all, you do at least get decent food out there.

1193
01:53:02,943 --> 01:53:05,570
Naturally, it's worse here. Naturally.

1194
01:53:06,029 --> 01:53:10,158
But the best for our soldiers
all the time. That's our motto.

1195
01:53:11,285 --> 01:53:12,994
The best for our soldiers.

1196
01:53:13,078 --> 01:53:14,787
The best for our soldiers.

1197
01:53:17,249 --> 01:53:19,542
But you must give the Frenchies a good licking !

1198
01:53:24,173 --> 01:53:26,966
And if you boys want to come home,

1199
01:53:28,594 --> 01:53:32,972
let me show you what you must do before you can come home.

1200
01:53:34,850 --> 01:53:36,893
Give us a hand there, men.

1201
01:53:37,436 --> 01:53:40,438
Now, then, there's the line.

1202
01:53:40,939 --> 01:53:43,483
Runs so, in a "V."

1203
01:53:44,443 --> 01:53:47,320
Here is St. Quentin. You can see for yourself.

1204
01:53:47,404 --> 01:53:49,947
You're almost through now. All right ?

1205
01:53:50,032 --> 01:53:54,452
Shove ahead out there and don't
stick to that everlasting trench warfare.

1206
01:53:54,995 --> 01:53:59,123
Smash through the Johnnies ! And then you will have peace.

1207
01:54:00,292 --> 01:54:04,295
When you get in it, the war
isn't the way it looks back here.

1208
01:54:04,379 --> 01:54:07,548
You don't know anything about it.

1209
01:54:07,633 --> 01:54:12,428
Of course, you know about the
details, but this relates to the whole.

1210
01:54:12,930 --> 01:54:14,722
You can't judge that.

1211
01:54:15,182 --> 01:54:18,809
Of course, you do your duty and you risk your life.

1212
01:54:19,144 --> 01:54:22,438
But for that, you receive the highest honor.

1213
01:54:23,649 --> 01:54:26,609
I said that every man in the
war ought to have the Iron Cross.

1214
01:54:26,693 --> 01:54:30,655
First, the enemy lines must be broken through in Flanders.

1215
01:54:30,739 --> 01:54:31,948
On to Paris !

1216
01:54:32,032 --> 01:54:33,324
Push on to Paris ! Right.

1217
01:54:33,575 --> 01:54:35,201
No, not in Flanders. Now I'll tell you

1218
01:54:35,285 --> 01:54:36,869
just where the break should come.

1219
01:54:36,954 --> 01:54:38,246
Here.

1220
01:54:38,330 --> 01:54:39,997
The enemy has too many reserves there.

1221
01:54:40,082 --> 01:54:42,041
I insist upon Flanders !

1222
01:54:42,125 --> 01:54:44,293
I know, but, my dear man, why should they do that

1223
01:54:44,378 --> 01:54:46,105
when they're halfway through St. Quentin already ?

1224
01:54:46,129 --> 01:54:47,255
Why go the other way ?

1225
01:54:47,339 --> 01:54:49,048
Because Flanders is a flat country.

1226
01:54:49,132 --> 01:54:50,883
There are no mountains, no obstructions.

1227
01:54:50,968 --> 01:54:52,635
But there's many rivers there.

1228
01:55:11,363 --> 01:55:13,531
From the farms they have gone,

1229
01:55:13,615 --> 01:55:16,200
from the schools, from the factories.

1230
01:55:16,618 --> 01:55:20,204
They have gone bravely, nobly, ever forward,

1231
01:55:20,581 --> 01:55:25,876
realizing that there is no other
duty now but to save the fatherland.

1232
01:55:27,087 --> 01:55:30,840
Paul ! How are you, Paul ?

1233
01:55:30,966 --> 01:55:33,050
Glad to see you, Professor.

1234
01:55:33,802 --> 01:55:37,888
You've come at the right moment,
Bäumer. Just at the right moment.

1235
01:55:38,098 --> 01:55:40,433
And as if to prove all I have said,

1236
01:55:40,517 --> 01:55:42,768
here is one of the first to go.

1237
01:55:43,145 --> 01:55:46,647
A lad who sat before me on these very benches,

1238
01:55:47,149 --> 01:55:50,610
who gave up all to serve in the first year of the war.

1239
01:55:51,111 --> 01:55:55,531
One of the iron youth who have
made Germany invincible in the field.

1240
01:55:55,866 --> 01:55:59,952
Look at him, sturdy and bronze and clear-eyed.

1241
01:56:00,245 --> 01:56:03,539
The kind of soldier every one of you should envy.

1242
01:56:04,499 --> 01:56:07,084
Paul, lad, you must speak to them.

1243
01:56:07,544 --> 01:56:11,172
You must tell them what it means to serve your fatherland.

1244
01:56:13,467 --> 01:56:15,051
No, no, I can't tell them anything.

1245
01:56:15,135 --> 01:56:17,595
You must, Paul. Just a word.

1246
01:56:17,679 --> 01:56:20,681
Just tell them how much they're needed out there.

1247
01:56:20,766 --> 01:56:23,851
Tell them why you went and what it meant to you.

1248
01:56:24,519 --> 01:56:26,145
I can't say anything.

1249
01:56:26,229 --> 01:56:30,941
Can't you remember some deed
of heroism, some touch of nobility ?

1250
01:56:31,360 --> 01:56:32,860
Tell about it.

1251
01:56:39,451 --> 01:56:42,161
I can't tell you anything you don't know.

1252
01:56:42,871 --> 01:56:45,790
We live in the trenches out there. We fight.

1253
01:56:47,000 --> 01:56:50,294
We try not to be killed, sometimes we are.

1254
01:56:53,173 --> 01:56:54,507
That's all.

1255
01:56:58,178 --> 01:57:00,638
No. No, Paul.

1256
01:57:01,098 --> 01:57:03,808
I've been there ! I know what it's like.

1257
01:57:04,017 --> 01:57:06,644
That's not what one dwells on, Paul.

1258
01:57:06,728 --> 01:57:09,897
I've heard you in here reciting that same old stuff,

1259
01:57:09,981 --> 01:57:13,067
making more iron men, more young heroes.

1260
01:57:14,194 --> 01:57:16,195
You still think it's beautiful and sweet

1261
01:57:16,279 --> 01:57:18,823
to die for your country, don't you ?

1262
01:57:18,907 --> 01:57:20,950
We used to think you knew.

1263
01:57:21,368 --> 01:57:24,078
The first bombardment taught us better.

1264
01:57:24,705 --> 01:57:27,707
It's dirty and painful to die for your country.

1265
01:57:27,791 --> 01:57:29,391
When it comes to dying for your country,

1266
01:57:29,459 --> 01:57:31,877
it's better not to die at all !

1267
01:57:31,962 --> 01:57:34,964
There are millions out there dying for their countries,

1268
01:57:35,048 --> 01:57:36,173
and what good is it ?

1269
01:57:39,594 --> 01:57:40,720
Paul.

1270
01:57:40,804 --> 01:57:43,889
You asked me to tell them how much they're needed out there.

1271
01:57:43,974 --> 01:57:46,225
He tells you, "Go out and die."

1272
01:57:46,393 --> 01:57:47,935
Oh, but if you'll pardon me,

1273
01:57:48,019 --> 01:57:50,855
it's easier to say, "Go out and die" than it is to do it.

1274
01:57:50,939 --> 01:57:52,231
Coward !

1275
01:57:52,315 --> 01:57:55,651
And it's easier to say it than to watch it happen.

1276
01:57:55,819 --> 01:57:57,361
Coward ! Get out !

1277
01:57:57,446 --> 01:58:00,239
No ! Boys, boys !

1278
01:58:01,658 --> 01:58:03,367
I'm sorry, Bäumer, but I must say...

1279
01:58:03,452 --> 01:58:05,536
It's no use talking like this.

1280
01:58:05,620 --> 01:58:07,663
You won't know what I mean.

1281
01:58:07,748 --> 01:58:11,917
Only, it's been a long while since
we enlisted out of this classroom.

1282
01:58:12,002 --> 01:58:16,005
So long I thought maybe the
whole world had learned by this time.

1283
01:58:16,173 --> 01:58:19,967
Only now they're sending babies, and they won't last a week.

1284
01:58:20,343 --> 01:58:22,511
I shouldn't have come on leave.

1285
01:58:22,637 --> 01:58:24,397
Up at the front you're alive or you're dead,

1286
01:58:24,421 --> 01:58:25,931
and that's all.

1287
01:58:26,016 --> 01:58:28,851
You can't fool anybody about that very long.

1288
01:58:28,977 --> 01:58:31,103
And up there we know we're lost and done for,

1289
01:58:31,188 --> 01:58:33,355
whether we're dead or alive.

1290
01:58:33,440 --> 01:58:36,150
Three years we've had of it... Four years.

1291
01:58:36,276 --> 01:58:39,361
And every day a year, and every night a century.

1292
01:58:40,322 --> 01:58:43,115
And our bodies are earth, and our thoughts are clay,

1293
01:58:43,200 --> 01:58:45,534
and we sleep and eat with death.

1294
01:58:45,869 --> 01:58:48,037
We're done for because you can't live that way

1295
01:58:48,121 --> 01:58:50,539
and keep anything inside you !

1296
01:58:50,624 --> 01:58:54,043
I shouldn't have come on leave. I'll go back tomorrow.

1297
01:58:54,336 --> 01:58:57,046
I've got four days more, but I can't stand it here.

1298
01:58:57,172 --> 01:58:58,881
I'll go back tomorrow !

1299
01:58:59,966 --> 01:59:01,133
I'm sorry.

1300
01:59:13,146 --> 01:59:16,482
Mother, you'll catch cold here. You must go to sleep.

1301
01:59:16,566 --> 01:59:20,528
There'll be plenty of time to sleep when you're gone.

1302
01:59:22,072 --> 01:59:25,199
Must you go tomorrow, Paul ? Must you ?

1303
01:59:25,742 --> 01:59:28,077
Yes, Mother. Orders were changed.

1304
01:59:31,331 --> 01:59:33,582
Are you very much afraid, Paul ?

1305
01:59:34,918 --> 01:59:36,335
No, Mother.

1306
01:59:38,880 --> 01:59:42,424
There's something I want to say to you, Paul. It's...

1307
01:59:43,593 --> 01:59:47,596
Just be on your guard against the women out there.

1308
01:59:48,598 --> 01:59:50,140
They're no good.

1309
01:59:50,934 --> 01:59:53,936
Where we are there aren't any women, Mother.

1310
01:59:55,313 --> 01:59:57,815
Be very careful at the front, Paul.

1311
01:59:58,483 --> 02:00:00,276
Yes, Mother, I will.

1312
02:00:00,652 --> 02:00:02,778
I'll pray for you every day.

1313
02:00:03,238 --> 02:00:08,450
And if you could get a job that's not quite so dangerous...

1314
02:00:10,745 --> 02:00:13,956
Yes, Mother. I'll try and get in the cookhouse.

1315
02:00:14,040 --> 02:00:15,249
That can easily be done.

1316
02:00:15,333 --> 02:00:18,085
You do it then, and if the others say anything...

1317
02:00:18,169 --> 02:00:20,296
That won't worry me, Mother.

1318
02:00:21,172 --> 02:00:22,381
Now you must go to bed

1319
02:00:22,465 --> 02:00:25,634
and you must get well quickly before I come back.

1320
02:00:27,846 --> 02:00:32,308
I put two sets of underwear, new ones, in your pack.

1321
02:00:32,934 --> 02:00:36,353
They'll keep you nice and warm. They're all wool.

1322
02:00:37,314 --> 02:00:38,981
That's sweet of you.

1323
02:00:39,941 --> 02:00:42,860
Good night, my son.

1324
02:00:51,161 --> 02:00:52,828
Good night, Mother.

1325
02:01:15,685 --> 02:01:19,480
Oh, Mother, Mother. You still think I'm a child.

1326
02:01:20,565 --> 02:01:23,692
Why can't I put my head in your lap and cry ?

1327
02:01:48,259 --> 02:01:49,426
Is this the 2nd Company ?

1328
02:01:49,511 --> 02:01:50,719
Yes, Sir.

1329
02:02:13,660 --> 02:02:14,702
Is this all of it ?

1330
02:02:14,786 --> 02:02:15,786
Yes, Sir.

1331
02:02:15,912 --> 02:02:19,289
We had 150 men, but this is all that came back yesterday.

1332
02:02:19,416 --> 02:02:23,002
But now they're going to give us enough to make 150 again.

1333
02:02:24,087 --> 02:02:25,546
How old are you ?

1334
02:02:26,256 --> 02:02:27,506
Sixteen.

1335
02:02:48,778 --> 02:02:51,238
No use. I couldn't find anything.

1336
02:02:51,781 --> 02:02:54,199
We'll have to eat the sawdust.

1337
02:02:54,617 --> 02:02:58,620
Not me ! I'll go hungry first. This makes me sick.

1338
02:03:14,554 --> 02:03:17,056
Now it's gonna be a real war again.

1339
02:03:17,807 --> 02:03:20,142
Paul ! How's old Paul ?

1340
02:03:20,560 --> 02:03:21,894
Here I am.

1341
02:03:22,312 --> 02:03:24,272
You know, the 2nd Company's getting hard to find.

1342
02:03:24,296 --> 02:03:26,899
Nobody seemed to know where you were.

1343
02:03:26,983 --> 02:03:28,817
I'm glad you found it.

1344
02:03:32,989 --> 02:03:35,449
I guess I don't get much of this.

1345
02:03:40,580 --> 02:03:44,583
There used to be some food in
the sawdust. Now it's all sawdust.

1346
02:03:44,667 --> 02:03:47,836
No joke, either. Eats you up inside.

1347
02:03:48,838 --> 02:03:51,423
This doesn't look much like the old 2nd Company.

1348
02:03:51,508 --> 02:03:53,133
The replacements are all like that.

1349
02:03:53,218 --> 02:03:55,928
Not even old enough to carry a pack.

1350
02:03:56,179 --> 02:03:58,472
All they know how to do is die.

1351
02:03:59,015 --> 02:04:02,351
I guess some of the old-timers are here yet.

1352
02:04:03,269 --> 02:04:07,106
Paul, they're trying to invent
something to kill me right now.

1353
02:04:09,150 --> 02:04:10,692
Where's Westhus ?

1354
02:04:11,694 --> 02:04:15,322
Messenger dog was wounded. He went out to get it.

1355
02:04:17,534 --> 02:04:19,243
Is it true about the armistice, Paul ?

1356
02:04:19,327 --> 02:04:20,953
Doesn't look that way back there.

1357
02:04:21,037 --> 02:04:22,788
You mean they want us to go on fighting ?

1358
02:04:22,872 --> 02:04:23,956
That's what they say.

1359
02:04:24,040 --> 02:04:25,499
They're crazy !

1360
02:04:27,293 --> 02:04:29,628
Germany'll be empty pretty soon.

1361
02:04:30,839 --> 02:04:33,006
Where's Detering ?

1362
02:04:33,842 --> 02:04:37,386
He got homesick. You remember about the cherry blossoms ?

1363
02:04:38,138 --> 02:04:40,389
I guess he never got over that.

1364
02:04:40,515 --> 02:04:42,015
He started out one night to go home

1365
02:04:42,100 --> 02:04:44,601
and help his wife with the farm.

1366
02:04:44,686 --> 02:04:48,397
They got him behind the lines,
and we never heard of him since.

1367
02:04:48,481 --> 02:04:52,484
He was just homesick, but
probably they couldn't see it that way.

1368
02:04:54,696 --> 02:04:56,321
Where's Kat ? Is he...

1369
02:04:56,406 --> 02:04:58,365
Not Kat !

1370
02:04:59,075 --> 02:05:01,368
If he were out, the war would be over.

1371
02:05:01,536 --> 02:05:03,120
You remember what he always says,

1372
02:05:03,204 --> 02:05:04,746
they're saving him for the last.

1373
02:05:04,831 --> 02:05:05,914
Where is he ?

1374
02:05:05,999 --> 02:05:07,291
He's out looking for food,

1375
02:05:07,375 --> 02:05:09,501
trying to collect something to make soup with.

1376
02:05:09,586 --> 02:05:11,128
Which way ?

1377
02:05:11,212 --> 02:05:13,255
Down the road about two miles that way.

1378
02:05:13,339 --> 02:05:15,048
I'll see you later.

1379
02:05:29,272 --> 02:05:30,314
Kat !

1380
02:05:35,111 --> 02:05:36,153
Paul !

1381
02:05:53,004 --> 02:05:54,421
Hello, Paul.

1382
02:05:56,090 --> 02:05:57,216
How's the side ?

1383
02:05:57,300 --> 02:05:59,509
Oh, it's all right now. It's fine.

1384
02:06:01,012 --> 02:06:02,137
Have any luck ?

1385
02:06:02,263 --> 02:06:05,807
No, the General's staff's been
over this country with a rake.

1386
02:06:06,809 --> 02:06:08,644
Let's sit down a minute.

1387
02:06:11,689 --> 02:06:14,983
Tell me, Paul, how was it at home ?

1388
02:06:15,443 --> 02:06:17,110
Have a good leave ?

1389
02:06:17,654 --> 02:06:18,737
In spots.

1390
02:06:18,821 --> 02:06:19,821
What's the matter ?

1391
02:06:20,865 --> 02:06:25,160
Oh, I'm no good for back there anymore, Kat.

1392
02:06:25,328 --> 02:06:28,664
None of us are. We've been in this too long.

1393
02:06:29,207 --> 02:06:31,959
The young men thought I was a
coward because I told them that

1394
02:06:32,043 --> 02:06:35,712
we learn that death is stronger than duty to one's country.

1395
02:06:37,006 --> 02:06:39,299
The old men said, "Go on. Push on to Paris."

1396
02:06:39,384 --> 02:06:41,843
My father even wanted me to wear my uniform around.

1397
02:06:44,847 --> 02:06:47,349
It's not home back there anymore.

1398
02:06:47,558 --> 02:06:52,020
All I could think of was, "I'd like
to get back and see Kat again."

1399
02:06:54,232 --> 02:06:56,525
You're all I've got left, Kat.

1400
02:06:56,859 --> 02:06:58,860
I'm not much to have left.

1401
02:06:59,529 --> 02:07:01,196
I missed you, Paul.

1402
02:07:01,656 --> 02:07:03,865
At least we know what it's all about out here.

1403
02:07:03,992 --> 02:07:05,867
There're no lies here.

1404
02:07:06,869 --> 02:07:08,537
Push on to Paris ?

1405
02:07:09,038 --> 02:07:11,498
You ought to see what they've got on the other side.

1406
02:07:11,582 --> 02:07:13,834
They eat white bread over there.

1407
02:07:13,918 --> 02:07:16,253
They've got dozens of airplanes to our one

1408
02:07:16,379 --> 02:07:18,880
and tanks that'll go over anything.

1409
02:07:19,382 --> 02:07:21,091
What've we got left ?

1410
02:07:21,551 --> 02:07:24,928
Guns so worn they drop shells on our own men.

1411
02:07:25,346 --> 02:07:28,557
No food, no ammunition, no officers.

1412
02:07:29,392 --> 02:07:31,018
Push on to Paris !

1413
02:07:32,186 --> 02:07:34,896
So that's the way they talk back there.

1414
02:07:36,566 --> 02:07:38,734
I guess we'd better be going.

1415
02:07:45,533 --> 02:07:47,743
How I lied to my poor mother.

1416
02:07:48,578 --> 02:07:50,912
I told her it wasn't so bad out here because

1417
02:07:50,997 --> 02:07:53,540
there was always a lot of us together.

1418
02:07:54,625 --> 02:07:56,001
Now that I'm with you,

1419
02:07:56,085 --> 02:07:59,129
I'm beginning to believe that I told her the truth.

1420
02:07:59,255 --> 02:08:00,380
Down !

1421
02:08:09,599 --> 02:08:12,309
That's another one that missed us. Come on. Let's go.

1422
02:08:12,435 --> 02:08:13,518
Wait a minute.

1423
02:08:13,603 --> 02:08:16,271
Looks like the old bread wagon's broke down.

1424
02:08:17,273 --> 02:08:19,483
I guess I don't walk the rest of the way.

1425
02:08:19,567 --> 02:08:20,817
Did that get you, Kat ?

1426
02:08:20,902 --> 02:08:23,111
I think it broke my shin.

1427
02:08:24,989 --> 02:08:27,783
That's not so bad. Hold it together.

1428
02:08:28,618 --> 02:08:30,410
Just my luck, huh ?

1429
02:08:30,495 --> 02:08:32,537
Good luck. That means the war is over.

1430
02:08:32,622 --> 02:08:34,456
Oh, no, Sir.

1431
02:08:34,791 --> 02:08:37,667
This war don't end till they really get me.

1432
02:08:38,920 --> 02:08:40,504
Now this one.

1433
02:08:41,089 --> 02:08:42,672
Easy, now.

1434
02:08:42,799 --> 02:08:43,882
Hey !

1435
02:08:44,008 --> 02:08:45,133
Easy !

1436
02:08:47,428 --> 02:08:50,305
Come on. I'll take you in. Give me your hand.

1437
02:08:53,351 --> 02:08:54,476
Easy.

1438
02:08:56,104 --> 02:08:57,437
All right.

1439
02:09:07,949 --> 02:09:11,326
Well, kid, now we're gonna be separated.

1440
02:09:12,203 --> 02:09:15,956
Maybe we can do something
together later on when the war is over.

1441
02:09:16,040 --> 02:09:17,249
Yes, kid.

1442
02:09:17,333 --> 02:09:19,418
You give me your address and I'll give you mine.

1443
02:09:26,217 --> 02:09:28,718
You can't get both of us in one day !

1444
02:09:29,679 --> 02:09:32,514
We'll surely see each other again, Kat.

1445
02:09:33,391 --> 02:09:37,310
Remember that day when you
brought the whole pig into the factory ?

1446
02:09:37,395 --> 02:09:41,398
And that day in the woods when
you taught us how to dodge shells ?

1447
02:09:41,691 --> 02:09:45,026
And my first bombardment. How I cried.

1448
02:09:46,362 --> 02:09:48,530
I was a young recruit then.

1449
02:09:52,368 --> 02:09:55,036
Here we are. Here we are.

1450
02:10:00,209 --> 02:10:02,043
All right now, Kat.

1451
02:10:05,214 --> 02:10:07,883
You could've spared yourself the trouble. He's dead.

1452
02:10:07,967 --> 02:10:11,219
Oh, no. He's just fainted. He was hit in the shin.

1453
02:10:11,387 --> 02:10:12,721
He's dead.

1454
02:10:26,652 --> 02:10:29,237
Would you like to take his paybook ?

1455
02:10:31,157 --> 02:10:32,824
You're not related, are you ?

1456
02:10:32,909 --> 02:10:34,576
No, we're not related.

1457
02:10:42,919 --> 02:10:45,337
Your deal. Did you get his name and number ?

1458
02:10:45,421 --> 02:10:48,256
Yeah, Corporal Stanislas Katczinsky, 306.

1459
02:10:55,932 --> 02:10:57,390
I don't get it.
